"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626027","Department of Health","false","2016-11-04","<p>Angioplasty for the treatment of angina is already available on the National Health Service.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-04T14:44:16.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626027/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626027/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Heart Diseases: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department is taking steps to make angioplasty available on the NHS to people with untreatable angina.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626028","Department of Health","false","2016-11-07","<p>No information is held centrally and no such assessment has been made by this Department.</p><p> </p><p>Eculizumab is not a licensed treatment for Dense Deposit Disease and well-constructed clinical trials on effectiveness are yet to be carried out. A new policy proposition for its use in treating the disease before a patient has had a kidney transplant will be considered during 2016-17.</p><p> </p><p>There is a published policy on use of this drug for the prevention of recurrence after a patient has had a transplant. A policy on the treatment of C3 glomerulopathy that occurs after a kidney transplant will be considered by the Clinical Priorities Advisory Group (CPAG) at its next meeting. CPAG reviews both patient benefits and cost considerations when making recommendations.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","51103","2016-11-07T12:18:18.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626028/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626028/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Dense Deposit Disease: Eculizumab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information he holds on the use of eculizumab to treat a patient with dense deposit disease at Evelina Children's Hospital.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","51102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626029","Department of Health","false","2016-11-07","<p>No information is held centrally and no such assessment has been made by this Department.</p><p> </p><p>Eculizumab is not a licensed treatment for Dense Deposit Disease and well-constructed clinical trials on effectiveness are yet to be carried out. A new policy proposition for its use in treating the disease before a patient has had a kidney transplant will be considered during 2016-17.</p><p> </p><p>There is a published policy on use of this drug for the prevention of recurrence after a patient has had a transplant. A policy on the treatment of C3 glomerulopathy that occurs after a kidney transplant will be considered by the Clinical Priorities Advisory Group (CPAG) at its next meeting. CPAG reviews both patient benefits and cost considerations when making recommendations.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","51102","2016-11-07T12:18:19.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626029/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626029/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Dense Deposit Disease: Eculizumab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the case of Abi Longfellow and her access to eculizumab for the treatment of dense deposit disease.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","51103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626030","Department of Health","false","2016-11-08","<p>No recent assessment has been made. It is for each local authority to decide the level and type of service to provide based on the needs of each individual and local circumstances and resources.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-08T09:11:08.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626030/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626030/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Disability: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of whether current levels of social care provision are sufficient to support young disabled people living independently.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","51099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626031","Department of Health","false","2016-11-07","<p>There is no central guidance on average home-to-hospital journey times for accident and emergency or maternity services. The redesign and delivery of front-line health services is a matter for the local National Health Service – clinically led by front-line NHS organisations and clinicians who are closest to the needs of their communities.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS is developing ambulance services that act as mobile assessment and treatment services and a networked approach to urgent and emergency care services to ensure patients are treated in the facility best equipped to provide whatever care is needed. For some patients requiring specialist care this may be in a hospital that is further away. NHS England has also asked Local Maternity Systems to develop plans that ensure women receive the maternity care that they want and need including, where women choose it, care in the community as close to home as possible.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-07T13:50:01.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626031/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626031/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Hospitals: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what average home-to-hospital journey time his Department uses as its benchmark for acceptable travelling time for patients using (a) accident and emergency and (b) maternity services.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","51117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626032","Department of Health","false","2016-11-08","<p>It is not possible to cross reference general practice (GP) appointments and GP clinical data to determine what clinical purpose any given appointment has; therefore, the Department cannot calculate how many GP appointments are used for diagnosing and treating mental health illness.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-08T09:10:13.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626032/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626032/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","General Practitioners: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the proportion of GP appointments that are currently used for diagnosing and treating mental health illness.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","51118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626033","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>The number of non-United Kingdom born nurses working in the National Health Service and social care is not collected by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital publishes data on the nationality of staff working in the NHS in England. The number of non-British nurses working in the NHS from 2009 to 2015 is set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-British Nurses and Health Visitors</p></td><td><p>36,941</p></td><td><p>38,026</p></td><td><p>37,453</p></td><td><p>36,641</p></td><td><p>37,025</p></td><td><p>39,922</p></td><td><p>43,716</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em> </em></p><p>Source: NHS Digital, NHS Hospital and Community Health Service workforce statistics.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>1. Figures are provided in headcount and at September of each year.</p><p>2. As nationality is self-reported, the value entered by an individual may reflect their cultural heritage rather than their country of birth. As such, these figures should be treated with a significant degree of caution.</p><p>3. These figures do not necessarily equate to migrants from other countries, and such data is not captured elsewhere in the workforce systems.</p><p>4. These figures exclude Moorfields Eye Hospital NHS Foundation Trust and Chesterfield Royal Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, who do not use the electronic staff record.</p><p>5. Nationally, over 95,000 NHS staff records do not contain useful data with people choosing not to specify their nationality or not asked to.</p><p> </p><p>Skills for Care (SfC), the partner in the sector skills council for social care, collects data on the nationality of nurses working in adult social care in England. SfC estimates on the number of non-British nurses working in adult social care is set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Years</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Registered nurses</p></td><td><p>20,000</p></td><td><p>19,000</p></td><td><p>18,000</p></td><td><p>17,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Skills for Care workforce estimates 2012-13 to 2015-16</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>1. This information refers to jobs working in the statutory local authority sector and the independent sectors only. Jobs for direct payment recipients and those working in the NHS are not included in these workforce estimates.</p><p>2. Independent sector information is derived from the National Minimum Dataset for social care (NMDS-SC) as at March 2013-16, local authority information is correct as at September 2012-15.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-03T14:29:45.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626033/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626033/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Nurses: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many non-UK born nurses have worked in the NHS and social care services in each year for which data has been collected.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","51121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626034","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>The following table shows the total number of people who enrolled as student nurses in each year in England for which data has been collected.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>1998-99</p></td><td><p>1999-2000</p></td><td><p>2000-01</p></td><td><p>2001-02</p></td><td><p>2002-03</p></td><td><p>2003-04</p></td><td><p>2004-05</p></td><td><p>2005-06</p></td><td><p>2006-07</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nurse Total</p></td><td><p>16,837</p></td><td><p>17,692</p></td><td><p>18,923</p></td><td><p>20,610</p></td><td><p>21,523</p></td><td><p>22,815</p></td><td><p>23,377</p></td><td><p>20,308</p></td><td><p>21,199</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nurse Total</p></td><td><p>19,352</p></td><td><p>20,664</p></td><td><p>20,829</p></td><td><p>20,092</p></td><td><p>17,741</p></td><td><p>17,219</p></td><td><p>17,568</p></td><td><p>19,147</p></td><td><p>19,949</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: multi professional education and training budget monitoring returns</p><p>Data on the number of applicants for University nursing training places is collected by the University and Colleges Admissions Service.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-03T14:34:40.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626034/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626034/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) people enrolled as student nurses and (b) applications were received for such enrolment in each year for which data has been collected.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","51122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626035","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>A time-series of total public capital spending against the Capital Departmental Expenditure Limit (DEL), since 2007-08, is recorded as an annex to the Department of Health Annual Report and Accounts 2015-16. The following table summarises the Capital DEL outturn for these years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>£000s</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-08</p></td><td><p>3,966,103</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>4,368,533</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>5,182,275</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>4,158,605</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>3,771,268</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>3,782,882</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>4,348,909</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>3,950,694</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>3,631,849</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Information relating to all Private Finance Initiative (PFI) projects in the National Health Service and social care in England is available on the Treasury’s website, via:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2015-summary-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2015-summary-data</a></p><p> </p><p>The capital cost figures are for the initial construction cost. The revenue payment figures include not just the financing costs (debt repayment and interest) for initial construction but also the costs of all the other services such as building maintenance and support services (cleaning, catering, portering etc) provided over the lifetime of the contract. The payments are subject to meeting agreed performance and quality standards and include an annual uprate assumption for inflation of 2.5%.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the latest published PFI revenue payments for hospital and social care schemes.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Revenue Payments 2014-15 (£ million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hospital and Acute</p></td><td><p>1,879</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Social care</p></td><td><p>63</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>1,942</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The recorded spend through Capital DEL includes expenditure on IT and equipment assets, whereas the spend recorded as PFI is focused on delivering serviced hospital buildings. Where buildings are delivered with Capital DEL funding they also incur significant costs in maintenance, cleaning etc but the Department does not retain a record of these costs.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-03T15:08:14.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626035/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626035/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the public purse has been of (a) capital and (b) private finance initiative projects in the NHS and social care services in England in each year for which data is recorded.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","51123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626036","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>Total agency spending in the National Health Service is available for the years 2013/14 to 2015/16</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Spending (£ billion)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>3.632</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>3.189</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2.589</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Data for the number of agency staff is not collected centrally; trusts publish individual accounts, which are publicly available.</p><p><strong><br> </strong>In a drive to increase transparency and performance, NHS Improvement is to begin publishing agency performance league tables in the coming weeks. NHS Improvement has written to trusts asking them to publish information about their 20 highest earning agency staff, and any agency staff who have been in post longer than six months.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-03T14:37:59.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626036/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626036/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","NHS: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many agency staff have been assigned to the NHS and social care services in England in each year for which data is available; and what the cost to the public purse of such staff has been in each such year.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","51124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626037","Department of Health","false","2016-11-07","<p>The then Minister for Public Health met Fertility Fairness and other stakeholders on 14 December 2015 to discuss the National Health Service provision of fertility services and, in particular, issues around the pricing of NHS in vitro fertilisation. Fertility Fairness has subsequently provided information and intelligence to the Department about current trends. A representative from Fertility Fairness is also closely involved in the work to develop a benchmark price for infertility treatments.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","51151 ; 51274","2016-11-07T17:56:10.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626037/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626037/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Fertility: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has had discussions with Fertility Fairness on clinical commissioning groups' adherence to NICE guidelines on the provision of NHS funded infertility services.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626038","Department of Health","false","2016-11-07","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Experimental data to monitor the waiting time target for people experiencing a first episode of psychosis has been collected by NHS England since December 2015 and is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/eip-waiting-times/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/eip-waiting-times/</a></p><p> </p><p>Some experimental data from the Mental Health Services Data Set relevant to waiting times standards is also published by NHS Digital. The most recent figures are at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://content.digital.nhs.uk/searchcatalogue?productid=23263&amp;returnid=1741" target="_blank">http://content.digital.nhs.uk/searchcatalogue?productid=23263&amp;returnid=1741</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-07T15:26:53.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626038/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626038/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the average waiting times for access to child and adult mental health services.","true","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","51043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626039","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>On 11 August the Home Secretary appointed Professor Alexis Jay as the Chair of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse. Professor Jay has been involved in the inquiry from the start. It is for everyone to support the Inquiry as it continues its vital work to uncover the truth, expose what has gone wrong in the past and learn lessons for the future.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-08T17:26:55.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626039/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626039/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps are being taken to ensure continuity in the child sexual abuse inquiry.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","51024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626040","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>The crime data integrity programme is a series of inspections by Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary of crime recording practice by police forces in England and Wales. The first round of inspections took place in 2014. The second phase is currently underway, and will see every force re-inspected to assess improvements in the quality and accuracy of their crime recording. The inspection programme does not affect the process for recording crimes, including those committed by young people, which should be recorded in line with the Home Office Counting Rules.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-08T16:21:47.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626040/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626040/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Crime: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for how long and by what method young people are recorded onto the crime data integrity programme.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","51033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626041","Home Office","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Home Office publish police use of TASER ® X26 statistics annually on GOV.UK. These releases contain statistics on police use of TASER ® X26 from the 43 Home Office police forces in England and Wales up to 2015.</p><p>The current TASER publications can be found at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/use-of-taser-statistics</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-23T16:38:27.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626041/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626041/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Stun Guns","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many tasers have been used by the police in the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626042","Home Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Government when developing the Hate Crime Action Plan (Action Against Hate) consulted with a range of stakeholders and community groups. This included the Independent Advisory Group on Hate Crime, a number of Police Independent Advisory Groups and a meeting of community stakeholders hosted by Greater Manchester Police on behalf of the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>The Government welcomes engagement with all faith representatives including the Sikh Community in taking forward the Hate Crime Action Plan and using it as a vehicle to tackle community concerns.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-04-26T09:35:35.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626042/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626042/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Sikhs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which UK Sikh organisations she consulted in the development of her Department's publication, Action Against Hate: The UK Government's plan for tackling hate crime, published in July 2016.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","51009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626043","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Public Sector Equality Duty (PSED) in the Equality Act 2010 ensures that public bodies take account of equality and consider the potential impact of decisions on groups with protected characteristics. All bodies exercising public functions who are subject to the PSED need to understand the impact of their policies and services on people with different protected characteristics and be able to provide evidence that this has been taken into account during the decision-making process. However, the legislation does not prescribe how this information needs to be recorded and it is not a statutory requirement in England to prepare or publish information in a particular form, such as an Equality Impact Assessment.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-08T17:28:56.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626043/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626043/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Home Office: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many equality impact assessments her Department carried out in each year between 2010 and 2016.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","50980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626044","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>The relevant guidance for caseworkers on HC2s for asylum seekers is contained in the Healthcare Needs and Pregnancy Dispersal policy document, which is available on GOV.UK at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/healthcare-needs-and-pregnancy-dispersal-instruction</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-14T15:43:38.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626044/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626044/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance her Department has issued to caseworkers on issuing and renewing HC2 forms for asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","50978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626045","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>Tier 2, the route for skilled non-EEA workers, is reserved for graduate level occupations only. Nurses, including those working in social care, are included on the Shortage Occupation List. Care workers do not meet the minimum skills requirement for Tier 2.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-14T15:44:03.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626045/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626045/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Migrant Workers: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will add care staff to the shortage occupation list.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626046","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>Information relating to Home Office officials who opt out of the Working Time Regulations is not held centrally. Collating locally held records could only be carried out at disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-08T17:28:38.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626046/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626046/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Home Office: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many officials of her Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626047","Home Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>Reforming the police funding formula remains a key priority for this Government and we are engaging with the sector to look at the options for taking this work forward.</p><p>We are clear that the size and makeup of the police workforce and how they are deployed will remain local decisions for Police and Crime Commissioners and Chief Constables.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-04T18:09:58.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626047/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626047/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Police: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has to maintain frontline police officer numbers in Cumbria under the revised funding formula.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","51173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626048","Home Office","false","2016-11-16","<p>The response to the Rt Hon.Member's letter of 29 September 2016 was issued on 3 November 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-16T17:33:11.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626048/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626048/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to reply to the letter of 29 September 2016 from the Rt hon. Member for Warley on QA Liftrucks Ltd.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","51188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626049","Home Office","false","2016-11-11","<p>The COMPASS contracts and their associated procurement exercise defined the required performance standards expected of all providers including sensitivity of equality impacts, these contracts are published at:</p><p>https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/503124/</p><p>The Government expects the highest standards from our contractors and providers are monitored closely to ensure they continue to meet these standards. Equality assessments have not been undertaken in isolation from usual contract tendering and management processes and discussions about equality impacts form part of regular engagement with stakeholder groups. Equality assessments are not collated in publishable formats.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-11T15:52:40.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626049/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626049/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2016 to Question 47816, if she will publish details of any (a) policy equality statement, (b) equality impact assessment and (c) equality monitoring that the Government has carried out on its contracts with Compass to provide accommodation to asylum seekers (i) prior to those contracts being signed in 2012 and (ii) in the years since those contracts were signed.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","51208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626050","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Workshop to Raise Awareness of Prevent training provides attendees with case studies to help build an understanding of how to recognise potentially vulnerable individuals who may be at risk of radicalisation, and how to share concerns so that the right support can be offered when it is required. All the case studies used in the training are based on real-life accounts. Feedback from attendees of WRAP training is consistently positive, and the content of the product is frequently revised and updated.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-12-08T18:56:33.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626050/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626050/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the list of vulnerabilities and warning signs tutors are advised to look out for as part of Workshop to Raise Awareness of Prevent training.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","51247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626051","Home Office","false","2016-11-29","<p>Prevent is a key part of the UK’s counter-terrorism strategy (CONTEST). Prevent safeguards and supports individuals who are vulnerable to exploitation for radical purposes. Prevent is working. It is has made a significant impact in preventing people being drawn into terrorism.</p><p>Working with industry and the police we have secured the removal of 220,000 pieces of terrorist material since February 2010. Since 2012, over 1000 people have received support through our Channel programme which safeguards those most at risk of radicalisation. More than 150 attempted journeys to the Syria/Iraq conflict area were disrupted in 2015. This includes action by the family courts. The courts have protected 50 children (from around 20 families) from being taken to the conflict area in 2015. To build resilience in communities against radicalisation in 2015/16, we have delivered 142 projects reaching over 42,000 participants.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-11-29T17:04:46.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626051/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626051/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Prevent Strategy in countering radicalisation.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","51248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626052","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Government has been working with the police and the motor industry to develop a clear and common understanding of the changing nature of vehicle theft, including through the compromise of modern electronic security systems. This has helped us to form a clearer and shared understanding with the police and industry of the methods used and what can be done to tackle these crimes, including through security improvements by manufacturers, targeted enforcement action by the police and changes in the way that consumers protect their vehicles.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-08T16:21:29.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626052/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626052/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Motor Vehicles: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to stop thieves using software to override keyless car entry systems to steal vehicles and contents.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","51236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626053","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>The Permanent Secretary at the Home Office advised the Home Affairs Select Committee on 18 October of the processes through which Dame Lowell Goddard was recruited.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-14T17:13:35.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626053/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626053/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-31","Independent Inquiry Into Child Sexual Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, who from her Department was involved in the recruitment process for the appointment of Dame Lowell Goddard to the post of chair of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse; and what the names were of the people on the interview panel.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","51273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626054","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-11-03","<p>The historic nature of the parliamentary estate means that newer buildings are more accessible than the older buildings for wheelchair users and people who need step-free access. While no estimate can be given of the number of rooms, those in Portcullis House and certain of the outbuildings have greater accessibility than the Palace and Norman Shaw buildings. Improving accessibility is being addressed as part of the Restoration and Renewal and Northern Estate Programmes, as well as the ongoing work across the estate.</p><p>Step-free access, as well as other access requirements, are a priority for the Commission. This year, we participated in the Business Disability Forum’s Disability Standard, which measures organisations against 10 criteria, including premises and adjustments. We increased our score from 42% in 2013 to 83%, achieving Silver accreditation. We have upgraded our membership of the BDF to Partner member, in order to make faster progress in becoming a ‘disability-smart’ organisation.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-11-03T17:30:18.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626054/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626054/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-10-31","Parliamentary Estate: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what estimate has been made of how many rooms on the Parliamentary estate are not wheelchair accessible.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","51170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626055","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>DFID’s Youth Agenda puts young people front and centre in the fight against global poverty. We are committed to working with young people, supporting them to be agents and advocates of change.</p><p>The UK is very concerned that adolescents are the only group, among HIV-affected populations, whose mortality figures are not decreasing. Many young people still lack access to information and services for sexual and reproductive health. In many countries, policies and laws explicitly exclude young people from sexual and HIV-related services.</p><p>The UK is committed to integrate the HIV response across all sectors for a truly comprehensive approach to end AIDS by 2030. Our work supports countries to find ways to enable safe, healthy and informed choices.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","51479","2016-11-07T16:02:02.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626055/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626055/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-31","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the need to tackle HIV and AIDS in its youth strategy.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626056","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>We have no record of any individuals employed by DFID who have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-07T15:50:11.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626056/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626056/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-31","Department for International Development: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many officials of her Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626057","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>HIV affects girls and women disproportionately, and a world without AIDS depends on a world where a girl’s rights and opportunities are protected. Until countries can work together to strengthen the sexual and reproductive rights of girls and women and deliver the services they need we will never achieve greater gender equality or end the AIDS epidemic.</p><p>AIDS is the leading cause of death for women of reproductive age - with an estimated 330,000 AIDS related deaths in sub-Saharan Africa in 2015 alone. This is why universal sexual and reproductive health and rights is a central pillar of DFID’s Strategic Vision. As a leading champion of sexual reproductive health and rights DFID takes the broadest possible definition which supports the integration of HIV with family planning and other SRHR services.</p><p>With UK support, gender equality is now a major pillar of the Global Fund’s Strategic Framework. The Global Fund invests an estimated 55-60% of its resources in programmes and services that reach women and children. DFID is also supporting the generation of new evidence to improve outcomes for women and girls, including supporting the development of female initiated HIV prevention technologies.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","51480","2016-11-07T15:59:07.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626057/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626057/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-31","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what priority her Department's strategy on women and girls accords to tackling HIV and AIDS.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","51142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626058","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>DFID does not track microloans separately from other financial inclusion programmes. DFID’s total investment in financial inclusion programmes is more than £426 million as of July 2016. The portfolio has a wide geographic spread with a focus on Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia. DFID focuses on ways to make business easier for micro and small enterprises to support growth and jobs, as opposed to a specific focus on microlending.</p><p>One of the best examples of our work with small businesses is DFID’s anchor investment of £75m in the Global Small and Medium Size Enterprise (SME) Finance Initiative established in 2012 along with other investors. As of June 2016, the programme had contributed to nearly £3.5bn of commercial loans supporting nearly 66,000 SMEs in 26 countries, including the Democratic Republic of Congo, Nigeria, Mozambique and Bangladesh. The programme has a particular focus on increasing finance to women-headed SMEs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-07T15:53:23.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626058/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626058/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-31","Developing Countries: Microfinance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, in which countries and for how many projects her Department provides microloans to local communities or small businesses.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","51237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626059","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules.</p><p>Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p>More broadly, the Government will be consulting in due course on how we work with business to ensure that workers in this country have the skills that they need to get a job. But there are no proposals to publish lists of the number or proportion of foreign workers.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-07T15:49:45.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626059/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626059/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-31","Department for International Development: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many citizens of non-UK EU countries work in her Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","51003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626060","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-07","<p>The information requested is published on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-07T16:44:24.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626060/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626060/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Pentonville Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) staff and (b) inmates there were at HM Prison Pentonville in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","50979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626061","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-24","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my response to PQ47590.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-24T17:03:06.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626061/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626061/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Ministry of Justice: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many citizens of non-UK EU countries work in her Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","51000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626062","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-30","<p>Since 2011, representations on HMP Pentonville have been received by the Ministry of Justice from the Independent Monitoring Board reports and from HM Chief Inspector of Prisons.</p><p>These reports can be found on the IMB and HMIP websites respectively. Both reports are public documents and therefore already available.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-30T12:37:42.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626062/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626062/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Pentonville Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what representations her Department has received on conditions at HM Prison Pentonville in the last five years; and if she will place those representations in the Library.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","50974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626063","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) provide rehabilitation and resettlement services to all offenders. We are committed to giving female offenders the help and support they need to reform and lead law-abiding lives and have been reviewing the services CRCs are providing for female offenders to ensure they meet contractual requirements. We are also working with partners in areas across England and Wales to develop whole system approaches to help female offenders turn away from crime and rebuild their lives. We will continue to robustly manage the CRC contracts to make sure they reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide the best value for money for the taxpayer.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-03T17:31:37.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626063/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626063/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Probation: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking in response to the conclusion of HM Inspectorate of Probation in its report of 29 September 2016, A thematic inspection of the provision and quality of services in the community for women who offend, that services for women are undervalued and under threat.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","50998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626064","Department of Health","false","2016-11-07","<p>NHS England is responsible for commissioning dental services in prisons, using a national service specification for the provision of prison dental services.</p><p> </p><p>The national service specification is currently under review as a result of prison reconfiguration. NHS England is working with the British Dental Association and National Association of Prison Dentistry UK to ensure that the updated specification meets the needs of the prison patient population.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-07T17:57:15.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626064/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626064/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-31","Prisons: Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the availability of dental services in prisons.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","51040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626065","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>Addressing the treatment of women with mental health problems in the justice system is vital. Liaison and Diversion services in the community enable clinicians to assess and refer those who have mental health needs to treatment and support at the earliest opportunity, ideally at their first point of contact with the criminal justice system. These services are currently being rolled out across the country. In prison, all new prisoners are assessed by a health care professional on arrival and, where appropriate, referred to a range of individual or group mental health interventions or substance misuse treatment interventions.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-08T15:59:30.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626065/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626065/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Administration of Justice: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what her policy is on the treatment of women with mental health problems in the justice system.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626066","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>It is vital that offenders are successfully reintegrated into communities if they are to turn their backs on crime and become productive members of society. Through-the-gate resettlement services delivered by Community Rehabilitation Companies mean that virtually all prisoners have access to targeted support to help them find accommodation and employment on release, and advice on finance, benefits and debt. To make sure that probation services are delivering improved outcomes for offenders and communities we are conducting a comprehensive review of the probation system.</p><p> </p><p>Prisons also have a vital part to play in preparing offenders for life after release, and close partnership working between prisons and probation is essential in making sure offenders are supported to reintegrate into society. Last week we set out our plans for prison safety and reform in order that custody better prepares offenders to lead law-abiding lives after release.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-08T16:09:39.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626066/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626066/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Prisoners: Rehabilitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness the Government's policy on reintegrating prisoners into society.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626067","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-20","<p>We are committed to helping offenders turn their lives around and to reducing reoffending. We know that providing advice and support to prisoners before release can help them settle back into the community on release and reduce the likelihood of their committing further crimes. At HMP Littlehey prisoners’ resettlement needs are identified and they have access to help finding suitable accommodation on release, setting up a bank account and finding employment.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-20T17:48:56.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626067/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626067/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Littlehey Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking to improve resettlement activity at HM Prison Littlehey.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626068","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>We will set out how the government intends to proceed in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-08T16:22:08.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626068/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626068/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Environment Protection: Civil Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when her Department plans to publish its response to the consultation on costs protection in environmental claims.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","51238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626069","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-10","<p>The table, below, represents the number of children that have been the subject of care order applications in England and Wales by age group, from 2011 – 2015, the latest year for which full data is available. Data on the number of care applications prior to 2011 is not held centrally.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1 - 4 years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>5 - 9 years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>10 - 15 years</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>16 years or more</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Unknown*</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>5,767</p></td><td><p>6,148</p></td><td><p>4,499</p></td><td><p>3,531</p></td><td><p>157</p></td><td><p>87</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>6,213</p></td><td><p>5,810</p></td><td><p>4,675</p></td><td><p>3,561</p></td><td><p>145</p></td><td><p>39</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>5,752</p></td><td><p>5,495</p></td><td><p>4,328</p></td><td><p>3,521</p></td><td><p>180</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>5,422</p></td><td><p>5,495</p></td><td><p>4,824</p></td><td><p>3,920</p></td><td><p>216</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>5,688</p></td><td><p>5,724</p></td><td><p>5,410</p></td><td><p>4,457</p></td><td><p>285</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong><em>* Unknown</em></strong><em> represents children whose age is null, this is when the date of birth is not entered or is entered incorrectly on the database. </em></p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-10T16:37:29.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626069/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626069/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Care Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many children (a) under one year old, (b) between one and four years old, (c) between five and nine years old, (d) between 10 and 15 years old and (e) 16 years old or more have been the subject of care order applications in each year since 2008-09.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626070","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>As the Justice Secretary announced in September, we will roll out pretrial cross examination for all vulnerable witnesses, including children, across all Crown Courts by the end of 2017.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-03T13:28:02.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626070/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626070/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Victim Support Schemes: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to her Department's report entitled Our Commitment to Victims, published in September 2014, whether the national roll-out of pre-trial cross-examination for child victims will be completed by March 2017.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","51255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626071","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>Protecting victims is our top priority. In 2015 we doubled the number of Registered Intermediaries, to increase the numbers available to help vulnerable witnesses and victims.</p><p> </p><p>The following table gives a breakdown of requests for Registered Intermediary (RI) support for the years 2010 to 2015 and the year to date 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Requests for RI support by year:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Requests Received</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1206</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1230</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1432</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>1797</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>3341</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>5503</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 (Jan – Oct)</p></td><td><p>5223</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-03T17:19:50.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626071/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626071/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Registered Intermediaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many requests were made for registered intermediaries in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","51226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626072","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-07","<p>There is no centrally held record of officials who opted out of the EU working time regulations and this information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. Our departmental policy is that staff may opt out of the 48-hour working time limit at any time. These staff members are then supported via local line management, who arrange for regular health and safety risk assessments to monitor the impact.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-12-07T09:20:36.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626072/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626072/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Ministry of Justice: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many officials of her Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626073","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-24","<p>Protocol 16 to the European Convention on Human Rights creates an optional system by which the highest national courts can choose to seek advisory opinions on the interpretation of the rights and freedoms under the Convention from the European Court of Human Rights. It will come into force once it has been ratified by ten High Contracting Parties to the Convention, and will apply only to those countries that have ratified it. It has so far been ratified by six countries.</p><p> </p><p>The Brighton Declaration on the reform of the Strasbourg Court covered a range of important measures and was a proud achievement for the United Kingdom. The Government of the day expressed its pleasure that it could help secure agreement for an optional system on advisory opinions in the Brighton Declaration for those States wishing to pursue the idea. However, the Government then and now has been clear that it is unconvinced of the value of advisory opinions, particularly for addressing the fundamental problems facing the Court and the Convention system. The Government therefore plans neither to sign nor ratify Protocol 16 at this time. If and when Protocol 16 comes into force, we shall instead observe how the system operates in practice, having regard particularly to the effect on the work load of the Court, and to how the Court approaches the giving of opinions.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","50960","2016-11-24T14:47:28.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626073/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626073/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions she has had with Cabinet colleagues on the implications of adopting advisory status of judgments of the European Court of Human Rights for UK membership of the European Convention on Human Rights.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","51086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626074","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>Local Authorities are statutorily responsible for working with and supporting an individual in order to assist them into securing settled accommodation, Additionally, as part of our probation reforms, all offenders get targeted support when they leave prison to help them reintegrate into society. This includes working with local partners to help them find accommodation.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for the percentage of prisoners who report that they were released into settled accommodation for the financial years 2010-11 to 2014-15 are published on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>From 1 May 2015 Community Rehabilitation Companies became responsible for helping offenders obtain suitable accommodation as part of their Through the Gate resettlement services. Information on what proportion of prisoners left prisons with settled accommodation for the financial year 2015-2016 and monthly information since April 2016 is not available centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-08T15:53:57.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626074/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626074/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Prisoners' Release: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of prisoners failed to find accommodation upon release in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626075","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government has no plans to withdraw from the ECHR.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","51299","2016-11-07T16:29:28.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626075/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626075/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what her policy is on the UK remaining a signatory to the European Convention on Human Rights.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","51087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626076","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>It is important to ensure that full and careful consideration is given to all of the relevant evidence. We will publish the conclusions of the review when that exercise has been completed and the findings collectively agreed by Ministers in the normal way.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-08T16:25:34.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626076/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626076/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 28 October 2016 to Question 49615, on Employment Tribunals Service: fees and charges, if she will provide further information on the progress made by the review; and how her Department defines the term in due course.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","51088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626077","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>The number of escapes for each prison in England and Wales is published annually on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-03T16:11:38.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626077/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626077/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Prisoner Escapes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoner escapes there were in (a) England and (b) Cumbria in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","51171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626078","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>Information on the full time equivalent staff in post in in HMP Haverigg, the only prison in Cumbria, is contained in the table below. Information on the number of prison officers in England is published regularly on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Full Time Equivalent Band 3-5 Prison Officers in Post at HMP Haverigg - 31 March 2011 to 2016</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Haverigg</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2011</p></td><td><p>134</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2012</p></td><td><p>131</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2013</p></td><td><p>113</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2014</p></td><td><p>103</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2015</p></td><td><p>111</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2016</p></td><td><p>130</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Safe prisons are fundamental to the proper functioning of our justice system. Our dedicated prison officers, who support tens of thousands of prisoners every day, are vital to the safe running of our prisons. We have recruited 2,900 staff over the last 12 months and are taking significant action to make sure we have appropriate staffing levels. As the Justice Secretary announced today, we will be investing in an additional 2,500 prison officers across the prison estate.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-03T16:15:56.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626078/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626078/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many full-time prison officers were employed in (a) England, (b) Cumbria and (c) Copeland constituency in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","51172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626079","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Government is committed to making sure that victims and witnesses of crime get the support they need and have the confidence to come forward, which is why we are rolling out recorded pre-trial cross-examination for vulnerable and intimidated witnesses. Roll out of the measure will start in January 2017 in Leeds, Liverpool and Kingston-upon-Thames Crown Courts, the courts where the pilot took place. It will continue to be rolled out in other Crown Courts during 2017.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-03T17:16:46.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626079/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626079/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Courts: Video Conferencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which locations her Department has identified as potential candidates for the first stages of the roll-out of section 28 of the Youth Justice Criminal Evidence Act 1999, announced in her Department's publication, Transforming Our Justice System, published in September 2016; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","51218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626080","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","The Government is committed to supporting and protecting victims and witnesses when they give their evidence. Since last year, we have established over 20 video live-link sites in England and Wales for vulnerable and intimidated witnesses to give their evidence away from the court building should they choose to do so.","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-03T13:32:13.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626080/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626080/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Victim Support Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to her Department's publication, Our Commitment to Victims, published in September 2014, what steps she has taken to ensure there are greater opportunities for vulnerable witnesses to give evidence at a location away from court.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","51219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626081","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-14","<p>The Government is committed to making the process of going to court simpler, easier and more sympathetic to victims. That is why we will roll out recorded pre-trial cross-examination in the Crown Court, to ensure vulnerable victims are spared the trauma of reliving events at trial.</p><p> </p><p>All publicly-funded advocates in sexual offences cases will be required to undertake specialist training on working with vulnerable victims and witnesses. Only advocates who have had the specialist training will be able to be instructed in and undertake sexual offences cases, including those in which video-recording of cross-examination features.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-14T17:39:36.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626081/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626081/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Sexual Offences: Victim Support Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Ministry of Justice paper, Our Commitment to Victims, published in September 2014, what plans she has made to ensure that all publicly funded advocates involved in serious sexual offences have undertaken approved specialist training on working with vulnerable victims; and whether her Department plans to update that training to take account of national roll-out of pre-trial cross-examination for vulnerable witnesses.","false","Biography information for Ann Coffey","Stockport","Ann Coffey","51202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626082","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-14","<p>HMP Littlehey has made good progress on implementing the recommendations set out in the unannounced report published in July 2015. Offender managers and supervisors assess pre-release needs and as part of a local initiative, two staff from the local CRC (BeNCH) support the referral to resettlement services. The policy response for managing the over 55 year old population has been reviewed. A range of sex offender treatment programmes as well as a Thinking Skills programme to assist with addressing the risks presented by this cohort of prisoners have been commissioned.</p><p> </p><p>The National Career Service (NCS) provides improved prisoner skills assessment and employment options on reception as well as group work sessions. Discharge clinics are provided by Healthcare to ensure forward planning of prisoner health and wellbeing on release.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-14T15:52:25.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626082/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626082/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Littlehey Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress her Department has made on implementing the reintegration planning recommendations outlined in the report on an unannounced inspection of HM Prison Littlehey  of March 2015.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626083","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government has concluded agreements with all three Crown Dependencies to provide UK law enforcement and tax authorities with unrestricted and near real time access to beneficial ownership information on corporate and legal entities incorporated in these jurisdictions from a central register or similarly effective system. The Crown Dependencies have committed to ensuring these arrangements will come into effect by June 2017, once the necessary legislation is in place.</p><p>There is already a significant level of cooperation between law enforcement agencies and authorities in the Crown Dependencies, and Jersey has had a central register of beneficial ownership since 1989.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-07T16:56:50.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626083/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626083/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626083/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, by what date she expects all UK Crown Dependencies to have adopted central registers of beneficial ownership accessible to UK law enforcement.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","51265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626084","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-08","<p>There has been significant progress in meeting the needs of female offenders since the publication of Baroness Corston’s 2007 report, the recommendations from which continue to inform our strategic direction for female offenders. We want to see fewer women entering the criminal justice system and in custody, and are working to ensure that at every stage of their offender journey, we are taking proper account of the specific needs of women, so that they receive the support they need to make positive changes in their lives.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-08T16:11:46.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626084/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626084/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Criminal Proceedings: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will implement the outstanding recommendations of the Corston report on the treatment of women in the criminal justice system.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626085","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-14","<p>I (Sam Gyimah) wrote to the chair of the Pentonville Independent Monitoring Board on 30 August in response to concerns raised in their report.</p><p> </p><p>As the Justice Secretary has made clear, there are a number of factors including the availability of psychoactive substances in prisons which must be tackled in order to make our prisons safe and places of rehabilitation.</p><p> </p><p>Staff at HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Pentonville are working hard to address the concerns raised in the report and liaising with local police to tackle the threat of drugs entering the prison. Ministers continue to keep the population level and conditions of HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Pentonville under review.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-14T15:56:35.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626085/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626085/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Pentonville Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to page 1 of the Independent Monitoring Board's Annual Report 2015-16 on HM Prison Pentonville, whether she has met that Board to discuss the conclusion that Pentonville urgently needs a timetable for its replacement or for reducing the population and upgrading the facilities.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","51252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626086","Scotland Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>On 25 October, the UK Government published its funding plans which underpin how the levy will operate in England. These plans will provide more support for younger apprentices and disadvantaged people, as well as more flexibility for employers. More details on the policy are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-apprenticeship-funding-to-transform-investment-in-skills" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-apprenticeship-funding-to-transform-investment-in-skills</a>.</p><p> </p><p>As skills policy is devolved, it is for the Scottish Government to decide how it will use its share of the funding.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-11-03T13:03:06.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626086/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626086/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626086/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-31","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether progress was made in discussions on the apprenticeship levy at the meeting of the Joint Ministerial Council on 24 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","51018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626087","Scotland Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>No officials in the Scotland Office have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-11-04T10:51:45.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626087/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626087/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-31","Scotland Office: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many officials of his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626088","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Department does not hold this information centrally. Opting out of the working time directive is approved on discretion of the authorising line manager.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-08T16:07:49.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626088/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626088/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Department for Transport: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many officials of his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626089","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Government is seeking a legally binding ban on scheduled night flights of six and a half hours at an expanded Heathrow. This would provide an extra hour and a half free from noise compared to today’s operation. The rules around the operation of night flight restrictions would be determined through consultation in line with the International Civil Aviation Organisation’s Balanced Approach to noise management. Furthermore, it is also expected that new binding noise targets and runway alternation arrangements would be consulted on with local communities as part of the planning process.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-03T12:17:34.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626089/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626089/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Heathrow Airport: Night Flying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 October 2016 to Question 50202, on Heathrow Airport: night flying, what (a) flexibility and (b) penalties for violation the Government plans to put in place in respect of the six-and-a-half hour ban on night flights from an expanded Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","51174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626090","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-03T12:01:54.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626090/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626090/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Trains: Graffiti","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many trains have been taken out of circulation due to graffiti in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","51189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626091","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that expansion at Heathrow benefits the whole of the UK and strengthens regional connectivity. The Government will set out mechanisms to protect and strengthen domestic services when it publishes a draft National Policy Statement in the New Year.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-03T12:22:33.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626091/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626091/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Heathrow Airport: Air Routes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer  of 28 October 2016 to Question 50200, on Heathrow Airport: air routes, what legal mechanisms the Government plans to use to protect existing domestic routes and provide additional connectivity across the UK with new routes from Scotland, Northern Ireland and the South West and North East of England.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","51175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626092","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-03","<p>We have a robust regulatory framework for drones to ensure the safety and security of our citizens. We continue to work closely with the CAA and industry to adapt and strengthen these regulations as drone use and the technology evolves. The detailed content for the Modern Transport Bill is currently being considered.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-03T13:39:19.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626092/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626092/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to include provisions on the regulation of drones in the Modern Transport Bill; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","51177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626093","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government is committed to a move towards zero emission road transport. This includes cars as well as other vehicles, such as buses. Our £30m Low Emission Bus Scheme is funding the delivery of over 320 Low Emission Buses – of which 86 are fully electric buses – from 2016 to 2019. A further £3.2m worth of supporting infrastructure will be funded under the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The Departments for Transport and for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs are working closely with the Committee on the Medical Effects of Air Pollutants, the Department for Health and Public Health England to consider all evidence on the medical impacts of air pollution. Our daily air quality forecasts provide health messages to the public based on the expertise of Public Health England.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-07T14:42:44.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626093/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626093/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Public Transport: Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to recent research on pollution particles potentially triggering Alzheimer's and other degenerative diseases, whether his Department has re-assessed the potential merits of measures to expand the use of electric-powered public transport.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","51027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626094","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Department for Transport does not currently have any formal plans in place to carry out a detailed assessment of trends in the level of the fuel efficiency of buses. We have however supported industry to create a new Low Emission Bus accreditation, which will help introduce buses with lower emissions and better fuel efficiency, to the UK bus fleet. Additionally, the Government will fund the purchase of over 300 fuel efficient Low Emission Buses under this accreditation, and will monitor their fuel efficiency.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-04T13:20:15.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626094/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626094/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Buses: Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 September 2016 to Question 44451, if the Government will carry out a detailed assessment of trends in the level of the fuel efficiency of buses.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626095","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Government has no plans to lower the drink drive limit. We believe that rigorous enforcement and serious penalties for drink drivers are a more effective deterrent than changing the drink driving limit.</p><p> </p><p>A fundamental review on drink and drug driving was commissioned in 2009. My Hon Friend can read the coalition government’s response here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-governments-response-to-the-reports-by-sir-peter-north-cbe-qc-and-the-transport-select-committee-on-drink-and-drug-driving" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-governments-response-to-the-reports-by-sir-peter-north-cbe-qc-and-the-transport-select-committee-on-drink-and-drug-driving</a></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-03T11:38:26.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626095/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626095/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Driving under Influence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of lowering the drink-drive limit to 50mg alcohol per 100ml blood.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","51013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626096","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-03","<p>Column i) in the table below gives the number of road deaths in reported road accidents in Wiltshire (including Swindon) in which at least one driver was known to be over the drink drive limit. This information is derived from breath tests carried out at the scene and blood alcohol content (BAC) levels from coroners’ reports.</p><p> </p><p>In some cases drivers may not have stopped at the scene and therefore were not given a breath test. In other cases drivers may have been killed but the Department has not been supplied BAC levels by the coroner. It is possible that some of these drivers could have been over the alcohol limit but it is impossible to know. The total number of people killed in accidents involving at least one driver in this group is provided in column ii). Column iii) gives the total number of road deaths in Wiltshire for context.</p><p> </p><p><strong>i) Number of road deaths in reported road accidents in which at least one motor vehicle driver known to be over the alcohol limit and ii) road deaths in accidents where it was not possible to determine whether a driver was over the alcohol limit: Wiltshire, 2010-2014</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>i) Known </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>ii) Unknown</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>iii) Total road deaths</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Data for 2015 will be available in August 2017.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-03T11:42:00.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626096/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626096/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Driving under influence: Wiltshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many deaths were caused in Wiltshire by people driving over the prescribed alcohol limit in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","51014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626097","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Department has not made a specific estimate of the proportion of High Speed 2 journeys that will be taken by passengers planning to fly through Birmingham International Airport. Modelling has estimated the number of passengers that will board HS2 trains at Birmingham Interchange in the future but does not specify what proportion of these will come from Birmingham Airport, the National Exhibition Centre or the existing rail station.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-07T13:13:50.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626097/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626097/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Birmingham Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the potential proportion of High Speed 2 journeys that will be taken by passengers who plan to fly through Birmingham International Airport.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","51031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626098","Wales Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Wales Office does not procure steel.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-11-03T13:17:47.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626098/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626098/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-31","Wales Office: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent estimate he has made of the level of procurement of British steel by his Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","51049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626099","Wales Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>No officials at the Wales Office have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-11-03T12:54:57.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626099/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626099/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-31","Wales Office: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many officials of his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626100","Wales Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>Inward investment continues to thrive in Wales. 2015/16 was the second best year on record for inward investment, with 97 new projects in Wales. These inward investment projects were from companies based in 23 countries around the world.</p><p>UK Government recognises the significant value to the Welsh economy from these investments - at least £660m - creating wider economic benefits, jobs and new business opportunities for Welsh companies through supply chains.</p><p>Lordan UK Ltd’s £1million investment into Wales is an example of the new investment opportunities that have arisen since the Israeli business delegation visit to Wales in 2015, which has generated further job and business growth.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-11-08T10:42:01.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626100/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626100/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-10-31","Investment: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of potential new investment opportunities between Wales and Israel since the Israeli business delegation visit to Wales in 2015.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","51147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626101","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-03T17:13:53.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626101/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626101/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-31","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people whose initial personal independence claim was unsuccessful died before their appeal was heard in each year from 2013 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","51216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626102","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Department does not keep records on this subject.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-08T17:37:13.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626102/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626102/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-31","Department for Work and Pensions: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many officials of his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626103","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-08","<p>Investment strategies in public sector pension funds are matters for the relevant trustees or local government administering authorities.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-08T16:54:11.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626103/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626103/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-31","Pension Funds: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to protect public sector pension funds from changes in the value of sterling (a) while the UK is negotiating to withdraw from the EU and (b) when the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","51195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626104","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-03","<p>Breakdowns of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) reassessment claims by type of clearance (i.e. whether the claim was awarded, disallowed or withdrawn), at the point of initial decision, are published online at https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk. This includes data on both the total number of PIP awards made and on such awards as a percentage of overall claims. It also includes breakdowns by month and by Local Authority.</p><p>These statistics run until July 2016. Figures are published on a regular basis and statistics for August to October will be available in due course.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","50929 ; 51225","2016-11-03T17:32:01.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626104/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626104/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-31","Personal Independence Payment: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of personal independence payment applications from addresses in the London Borough of Newham were accepted at the first stage without submitting a mandatory reconsideration or appeal between April 2015 and October 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","51223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626105","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-03","<p>The role of contracted Assessment Providers is to carry out assessments on behalf of the Department. They do not determine whether a claim to Personal Independence Payment or Employment and Support Allowance is successful. They provide a report to DWP’s decision makers who then determine entitlement to benefit. No targets are in place as to how many applications are successful.</p><p>Where a need for additional support or training is identified, feedback is provided to the assessor and appropriate action taken.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","51156","2016-11-03T16:49:18.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626105/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626105/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-31","Work Capability Assessment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department's assessment contractors receive any penalty or fine when a claimant has been initially refused (a) personal independence payment and (b) employment and support allowance and is later awarded the relevant benefit on appeal at tribunal.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","51158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626106","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-03","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p><br>Information in respect of Employment and Support Allowance work capability assessments can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/employment-and-support-allowance-outcomes-of-work-capability-assessment.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-03T16:58:33.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626106/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626106/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-31","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employment and support allowance (ESA) claimants with (a) chronic disabilities and (b) illnesses were declared fit to work and had their ESA payments stopped in each month of (i) 2013, (ii) 2014, (iii) 2015 and (iv) 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","51157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626107","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-08","<p>The upper limit (annual cap) was announced in March 2015 and came into effect, for new customers only, in October 2015. New applications made between October 2015 and March 2016 were capped at an annual limit of £40,800, meaning that new customers could still potentially receive an award of £122,400 over a three year period. The annual cap was increased to £41,400 with effect from April 2016 and will continue to be reviewed annually.</p><p> </p><p>Those existing customers whose awards are or were above the annual cap have been notified that they will retain their current award, subject to usual annual reviews, until April 2018, provided their needs remain the same.</p><p> </p><p>In the meantime, Access to Work specialist teams are conducting annual reviews with customers and employers to establish the level of support required and determine whether there are any reasonable adjustments or other changes, such as greater use of technology, that could assist the customer overcome the barriers they face. Where appropriate, Access to Work will also commission a holistic workplace assessment of an individual’s support needs.</p><p> </p><p>We will monitor the application of the cap and consider whether any further flexibilities might be required in practice.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-08T17:23:02.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626107/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626107/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-31","Access to Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department is putting in place to support people currently in receipt of Access to Work awards over the annual cap and their employers to prepare them for the end of the transition phase of the annual cap for existing scheme users.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","51055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626108","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-03","<p>The role of contracted Assessment Providers is to carry out assessments on behalf of the Department. They do not determine whether a claim to Personal Independence Payment or Employment and Support Allowance is successful. They provide a report to DWP’s decision makers who then determine entitlement to benefit. No targets are in place as to how many applications are successful.</p><p>Where a need for additional support or training is identified, feedback is provided to the assessor and appropriate action taken.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","51158","2016-11-03T16:49:18.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626108/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626108/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-31","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department's assessment contractors received any (a) penalty, (b) bonus and (c) incentive to deny individual claims for (i) personal independence payment and (ii) employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","51156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626109","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-08","<p>As at June 2016, there were 1730 parents with care in the Inverclyde constituency that have a case with the Child Support Agency. As at June 2016, there were 1740 non-resident parents in the Inverclyde constituency that have a case with the Child Support Agency.</p><p> </p><p>Information on geographical breakdowns on the Child Maintenance Scheme is not routinely recorded for management information purposes and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p>1) Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10.</p><p>2) Cases have been allocated to a parliamentary constituency by matching the residential postcode of the parent with care or non-resident parent for all cases administered on the CS2 and CSCS computer systems and cases managed off system to the Office for National Statistics Postcode Directory.</p><p>3) Parents with Care and Non Resident Parents might have more than one case so an individual may be included in the figures more than once.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-08T14:27:59.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626109/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626109/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-31","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) parents with care and (b) non-resident parents there are in Inverclyde constituency with a current (i) Child Support Agency case and (b) child maintenance case.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","51094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626110","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-03","<p>Information on all the contractual targets, payments and penalties for Personal Independence Payment and Employment Support Allowance assessment contractors can be found on the Government’s Contract Finder website:</p><p>Atos Healthcare for PIP assessments in Northern England and Scotland – Lot 1<br>http://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/695721/</p><p>Capita for Central England and Wales assessments – Lot 2 <br>http://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/740844/</p><p>Atos Healthcare for PIP assessments in London, East of England and Southern England – Lot 3<br>http://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/695729/</p><p>Capita for Northern Ireland assessments – Lot 4<br>http://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/762330/</p><p>Health and Disability Assessment Service (ESA)<br>https://online.contractsfinder.businesslink.gov.uk:443/Common/View%20Notice.aspx?site=1000&amp;lang=en&amp;NoticeId=1644334</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-03T17:02:16.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626110/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626110/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-31","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what targets his Department's assessment contractors have  for conducting (a) personal independence payments and (b) employment and support allowance assessments.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","51155"
