"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626130","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-03","<p>We are currently analysing responses to the consultation on reforms to the Renewable Heat Incentive and will be publishing a formal response in due course.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-03T17:28:11.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626130/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626130/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Solar Power: Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to announce the results of the consultation on proposals to remove solar panels from the Renewable Heat Incentive scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","51017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626131","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-08","<p>The UK will maintain its status as a global centre for research and innovation. In last year’s Spending Review the Government committed to protecting science resource funding in real terms from its 2015-16 level of £4.7 billion a year for the rest of the parliament, as well as committing to invest in new scientific infrastructure on a record scale – £6.9 billion over the period 2015-2021.</p><p>While the UK remains a member of the EU, funding and collaboration arrangements continue unchanged. Researchers can continue to bid for competitive EU research funding such as Horizon 2020 while we remain a member of the EU. The Government will work with the Commission to ensure payment when funds are awarded. The Treasury will underwrite the payment of such awards, even when specific projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU. Access to apply to Horizon 2020 and subsequent funding programmes after we leave the EU will be a matter for the negotiations that will follow the triggering of Article 50.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-11-08T14:35:33.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626131/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626131/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government has made an assessment of future levels of research funding in the UK after the UK leaves the EU and existing projects have been completed.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","51022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626132","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the response given on 12 September 2016 by the Minister of State, my hon. Friend the Member for Orpington (Joseph Johnson) to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-09-12/45898/" target="_blank">45898</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-11-07T14:44:19.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626132/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626132/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many citizens of non-UK EU countries work in his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","51001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626133","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) is placing equality at the heart of all policy and decision making.</p><p>To comply with the Equality Act 2010, BEIS, and the former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS), assesses all key policies and decisions for any likely impact on individuals or groups with protected characteristics, and decisions are recorded.</p><p>There is no requirement for public bodies to keep a record of the number of assessments carried out. However, those that were published, for former BIS, can be found located alongside technical and economic Impact Assessments at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?commit=Refresh+results&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-innovation-skills&amp;from_date=&amp;keywords=&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;page=2&amp;publication_filter_option=impact-assessments&amp;to_date=&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?commit=Refresh+results&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-business-innovation-skills&amp;from_date=&amp;keywords=&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;page=2&amp;publication_filter_option=impact-assessments&amp;to_date=&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all</a>.</p><p>No equality impact assessments have been published since the inception of BEIS.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-11-07T14:43:15.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626133/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626133/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many equality impact assessments his Department carried out in 2016; and how many such assessments the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills carried out in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","50981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626134","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-03","<p>In its role as Guarantor, the Government has received £3,356.3m from the Mineworkers’ Pension Scheme since 1994. No payments have been made into the scheme by the Government. The existing surplus-sharing arrangements have worked well to date, with the presence of the Guarantee enabling the Trustees to invest in a way that has generated surpluses and, as a consequence, bonuses to members.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-03T16:32:20.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626134/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626134/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Mineworkers' Pension Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2016 to Question 48677, how much the Government has received from the Mineworkers' Pensions Scheme since 1994 net of payments from the Government arising from its guarantee.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","51065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626135","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-04","<p>Since 2011 the Government has invested over £130 million through innovation support to help develop carbon capture technologies and reduce their costs. This includes spending approximately £11 million since 2015 on a range of carbon capture projects supporting research and development in CO<sub>2</sub> storage, carbon capture technologies and CCS feasibility studies. The Government Energy Entrepreneurs Fund has funded approximately £1.6 million in support to innovative carbon capture technologies. Phase 5 of this Fund opened on 30 October 2016. This is an additional £9 million of funding which is open to carbon capture projects and further information can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/energy-entrepreneurs-fund-phase-5" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/energy-entrepreneurs-fund-phase-5</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-04T10:55:39.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626135/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626135/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626135/answer/previousversion/18588","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Carbon Capture and Storage: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what research is being conducted by the Government on carbon capture technologies.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","51064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626136","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-03","<p>No payments have been made into the scheme by the Government.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-03T16:36:41.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626136/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626136/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Mineworkers' Pension Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government has made direct payments to the Mineworkers' Pension Scheme under the guarantee arrangements.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","51063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626137","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-03","<p>We are committed to ensuring that high streets throughout the country remain at the heart of their community and we have taken significant actions to help high streets adapt and thrive through a range of targeted tax breaks, sensible planning changes and measures to ensure fairer parking for motorists.</p><p>At Budget 2016 we announced the biggest ever cut in business rates – worth £6.7 billion across the next five years. The Government is permanently doubling the level of Small Business Rate Relief and increasing the thresholds to benefit a greater number of property occupiers. Eligible properties with a rateable value of £12,000 and below will receive 100% relief. This means that 600,000 small businesses will pay no business rates at all, including local high street shops. Furthermore, the revaluation of Business Rates will ensure business rate bills more closely reflect the property market and that all businesses are getting a fair deal. The revaluation will reduce bills in the West Midlands by 7% before inflation and transitional relief. This will reduce bills by almost £170m per year. The biggest winners are in offices which will see bills falls by 16% and retail which will see bills fall by 11%.</p><p>We have also given over £18 million to town teams since 2010, including Redditch, funding successful initiatives such “Love Your Local Market” and the “Great British High Street Competition”. The finalists for the 2016 Awards include Derby, Hinckley, Market Harborough, Bridgnorth, and Leominster. The winners will be announced in December.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-11-03T11:17:39.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626137/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626137/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Retail Trade: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has for invigorating high street trading in the West Midlands in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","51029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626138","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-04","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy meets regularly with energy industry leaders. A register of meetings is published on a quarterly basis as part of the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy’s transparency data.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-04T14:54:39.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626138/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626138/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Fracking: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with industry on hydraulic fracturing in the North West.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","51097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626139","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Department last published estimates of the efficiency of different technologies in 2013 [1]. As the design of many of these technologies is rapidly changing, we expect to publish an update of the evidence in due course.</p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/energy-generation-cost-projections" target="_blank"><em>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/energy-generation-cost-projections</em></a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-08T14:56:35.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626139/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626139/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the relative efficiency of combined cycle gas turbines and reciprocating gas and diesel engines.","false","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","51205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626140","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-08","<p>The prequalification results for the 2016 four-year ahead Capacity Market auction have been published on the Electricity Market Reform Delivery Body’s website[1]. Around a quarter of the pre-qualified capacity is new-build, and nearly half of this is from combined cycle gas turbines (CCGTs). Approximately 6.1GW of reciprocating engines (existing and new) have also prequalified.</p><p> </p><p>The competitive nature of the auction means it is difficult to predict accurately the specific technologies and projects that will win agreements. CCGTs and gas reciprocating engines differ with respect to their cost and revenue profiles, with both technologies able to play a valuable role in the electricity market – CCGTs are highly efficient at providing baseload generation, whereas gas reciprocating engines are highly flexible and useful for helping balance the electricity system. Both will also compete against new interconnection, storage and demand-side response bids.</p><p> </p><p>My department has been working – as have Ofgem and Defra – to address potential distortions in the wider market and so ensure all projects compete on a level playing field.</p><p>A mix of new build technologies, in addition to existing capacity, could win, with competition bearing down on the auction cost to deliver value for money for the consumer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.emrdeliverybody.com/CM/prequalification.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.emrdeliverybody.com/CM/prequalification.aspx</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","51203","2016-11-08T17:59:32.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626140/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626140/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) number of gas or diesel reciprocating engines and (b) generating capacity likely to qualify in the T4 Capacity Market auction.","false","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","51204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626141","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Government is clear that the misuse of laser pointers against transport operators presents serious safety concerns. That is why my Department is looking into legislative options to address the misuse of laser pointers against aircraft and other modes of transport.</p><p> </p><p>My officials will continue to work with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and the Home Office in tackling this important issue and ensuring public safety.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-03T12:13:26.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626141/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626141/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-31","Lasers: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for Climate Change and Industry of 13 September 2016, Official Report, columns 757-8, what progress the Government has made on assessing options to help tackle the misuse of laser pens (a) on aircraft, (b) on transport infrastructure and (c) generally.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626142","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-07","<p>Approximately 6.1GW of reciprocating engines have prequalified for the 2016 four-year ahead Capacity Market auction.</p><p>Reciprocating engines emit less carbon per unit of generation than coal-fired power stations. They can also emit less carbon than larger gas-fired generation plants under certain conditions [1].</p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> National Physical Laboratory (2015): Carbon savings of demand side response of a UK energy</em></p><p><em>aggregator <a href="http://www.npl.co.uk/content/ConPublication/6739" target="_blank">http://www.npl.co.uk/content/ConPublication/6739</a></em></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-07T12:00:26.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626142/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626142/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many sub-1000MW reciprocating engines have prequalified for the Third T4 Capacity Market auction; and whether his Department has made an assessment of the effect of such pre-qualifications on the UK's ability to meet its carbon emission targets.","false","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","51207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626143","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-09","<p>Around 0.7GW and 0.9GW of reciprocating engines won 15-year agreements in the four-year ahead Capacity Market auctions in 2014 and 2015 respectively.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-09T15:36:49.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626143/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626143/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what gigawatt capacity of gas or diesel reciprocating engines won 15-year contracts in the first two T4 Capacity Market auctions.","false","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","51206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626144","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-03","<p>Before shale operations begin, it is important that a developer is required to obtain all the necessary permissions, including planning and environmental permits.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has an effective planning system to consider and scrutinise unconventional oil and gas developments. On 16 September 2015, the Government published a joint Written Ministerial Statement[1] to make the planning system faster and fairer for those affected by new development, recognising that no one benefits from uncertainty caused by delay. We will keep the regulatory regime for shale under review as the industry develops to ensure it is proportionate and fit for purpose.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-09-16/HCWS202/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-09-16/HCWS202/</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-03T16:35:14.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626144/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626144/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make it his policy to simplify planning and administrative processes required before exploratory drilling can take place for shale gas.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","51120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626145","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not record centrally the number of officials who have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive and can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-11-03T10:48:47.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626145/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626145/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many officials of his Department have opted out of the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","51125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626146","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-08","<p>The prequalification results for the 2016 four-year ahead Capacity Market auction have been published on the Electricity Market Reform Delivery Body’s website[1]. Around a quarter of the pre-qualified capacity is new-build, and nearly half of this is from combined cycle gas turbines (CCGTs). Approximately 6.1GW of reciprocating engines (existing and new) have also prequalified.</p><p> </p><p>The competitive nature of the auction means it is difficult to predict accurately the specific technologies and projects that will win agreements. CCGTs and gas reciprocating engines differ with respect to their cost and revenue profiles, with both technologies able to play a valuable role in the electricity market – CCGTs are highly efficient at providing baseload generation, whereas gas reciprocating engines are highly flexible and useful for helping balance the electricity system. Both will also compete against new interconnection, storage and demand-side response bids.</p><p> </p><p>My department has been working – as have Ofgem and Defra – to address potential distortions in the wider market and so ensure all projects compete on a level playing field.</p><p>A mix of new build technologies, in addition to existing capacity, could win, with competition bearing down on the auction cost to deliver value for money for the consumer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.emrdeliverybody.com/CM/prequalification.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.emrdeliverybody.com/CM/prequalification.aspx</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","51204","2016-11-08T17:59:32.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626146/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626146/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-31","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what analysis his Department has made of the effect of reciprocating gas and diesel generation on (a) the likely Third T4 auction price and (b) the likelihood of securing new combined cycle gas turbine generation capacity.","false","Biography information for James Heappey","Wells","James Heappey","51203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626147","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that, as we leave the EU, we will make Britain a country that truly works not just for a privileged few, but for everybody.</p><p>Dialogue with civil society will play a vital role in informing the development of the UK’s approach to trade. Over the coming weeks and months we will be engaging with a wide range of stakeholders, including civil society groups, both in the UK and internationally.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-03T17:11:28.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626147/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626147/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to establish and facilitate civil society dialogue when negotiating trade agreements between the UK and other countries (a) during negotiations on the UK leaving the EU and (b) after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","51217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626148","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-08","<p>The UK and Israel have a strong and important trading relationship and the pharmaceutical sector is strategically important for the United Kingdom. Whilst it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions at this stage, we are committed to working towards a smooth transition for businesses to minimise disruption to exports and investment as we leave the EU.</p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-08T13:47:46.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626148/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626148/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Trade Agreements: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to ensure that the UK secures a trade agreement with Israel for pharmaceutical products after the UK ceases to be party to the EU-Israel mutual recognition agreement on pharmaceutical certificates.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","51148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626149","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-08","<p>UK Trade and Investment, now known as the Department for International Trade, was actively involved in assisting 29 Israeli companies to set up or expand their operations in the UK and create 560 new UK jobs in 2015.</p><p>The UK is the number one destination for Israeli FDI in Europe and there are now more than 300 Israeli companies established in the UK.</p><p>Israel is an important trading partner for the UK and we are committed to further strengthening our trade and investment relationship.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-08T17:28:45.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626149/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626149/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Foreign Investment in UK: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many jobs were created in the UK by Israeli companies in 2015; and what steps his Department is taking to encourage more Israeli companies to trade in the UK.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","51251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626150","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Government is currently reviewing its trade policy as the UK prepares to leave the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate and design, in time, our own trade arrangements. We recognise the need for a smooth transition which minimises disruption to our trading relationship with African countries.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-08T16:26:25.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626150/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626150/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Overseas Trade: Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with which African countries his Department plans to prioritise trade deals after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","51107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626151","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>More trade is essential in order to promote economic growth and reduce poverty. Promoting trade in Africa offers tremendous opportunities, both to African and British businesses. Now and after leaving the EU, the UK will continue the work started by the African Free Trade initiative to support trade in Africa by providing assistance to improve infrastructure, cut red tape and harmonise regulations, and increase businesses’ capacity to export.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-07T16:04:07.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626151/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626151/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-31","Free Trade: Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of launching a second phase of the Africa Free Trade initiative after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","51108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626152","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-07","<p>The UK is firmly supportive of the aims of the Continental Free Trade Area. The creation of a single continental market for goods and services, the expansion of intra-African trade, and enhanced competitiveness of industry will all help to boost economic growth, reduce poverty and strengthen UK trade and investment opportunities.</p><p>The timetable for establishing the CFTA is ambitious and we would encourage the AU and African countries not to lose sight of the need to strengthen implementation of existing agreements, especially on trade facilitation.</p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-07T16:09:17.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626152/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626152/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-31","Free Trade: Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her policy is on the development of an African Union Continental Free Trade Area.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","51104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626153","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-08","<p>The Department for International Trade is working with others to understand the issues which African countries face in implementing the World Trade Organisation (WTO) Agreement on Trade Facilitation and to encourage ratification of the Agreement by all WTO Members. The UK, through the Department for International Development, has committed nearly £180 million between 2013 and 2022 to support African and other developing countries to implement this Agreement to reduce red tape at the border.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-08T13:49:04.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626153/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626153/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Overseas Trade: Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to promote the ratification of World Trade Organisation rules and improve border and custom clearance procedures within the African continent.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","51105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626154","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Government will continue to follow a science-based policy on genetically modified organisms, including in relation to imports.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-04T14:27:55.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626154/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626154/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-31","Genetically Modified Organisms: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her policy is on importing genetically modified organisms after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","51106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626155","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-03","<p>Details of the Department for International Trade’s handling of requests under the Freedom of Information Act from the Department’s formation until 30 September 2016 will be published by the Cabinet Office later this year on <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.Gov.uk</a>. Statistics for quarter four of the year (October – December 2016) will be published at the same location in the New Year.</p><p> </p><p>As official statistics, disclosure of the information prior to its publication is prohibited by the Statistics and Registration Services Act 2007 and the Pre-release Access to Official Statistics Order 2008.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-03T17:12:45.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626155/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626155/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Department for International Trade: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many freedom of information requests have been submitted to his Department since July 2016; how many such requests the Department has responded to; how many such requests the Department has responded to within 20 working days; and for what number of days the longest outstanding request has been awaiting response.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","51062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626156","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 250 staff plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels, and we are still growing rapidly. We are not in a position to give a final total as recruitment is ongoing.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-11-03T15:41:47.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626156/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626156/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-31","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff in his Department are currently on loan from the Ministry of Defence.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","51011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626157","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-08","<p>As we conduct our negotiations to leave the EU, we will aim to obtain the best deal for the British people. We will consider all options that are available to us, including those on mobile roaming.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-08T17:23:41.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626157/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626157/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Mobile Phones: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department plans to ensure that UK residents continue to be subject to caps on mobile telephone roaming charges when abroad after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Rupa Huq","Ealing Central and Acton","Dr Rupa Huq","51196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626158","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-11-03","<p>We are continuing our analysis of the UK economy. We will not however publish any analysis that might risk harming our negotiating position.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-11-03T12:37:36.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626158/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626158/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-31","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 27 October 2016 to Question 49977, on UK withdrawal from the EU, when he expects the analysis of the UK economy to be completed; and if he will make it his policy to publish the results of that analysis upon its completion.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","51181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626159","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-11-03","<p>We have been clear that we want to create an environment in which the UK as a whole can continue to be a world leader in research, science and the tertiary education sector more broadly.</p><p>We are engaging with the Governments of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland to ensure a UK-wide approach to our negotiations. Details of Ministerial meetings will be published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which will be made publicly available on GOV.UK.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-11-03T12:47:12.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626159/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626159/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-31","Higher Education: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the higher education sector in Scotland of the UK leaving the EU; what recent discussions his Department has had with Ministers of the Scottish Government on that potential effect; and what assessment his Department has made of the availability of different options for the higher education sector in Scotland after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","51228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626160","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-11-03","<p>Current EU students and the 16/17 and 17/18 cohorts have already had reassurance that they will be able to obtain finance for the full duration of their course. Applications for 18/19 do not open until September 2017 and we will ensure students applying have information in advance of this date. We are not going to provide a running commentary on every twist and turn of the negotiations, but we will work hard to get the best deal for Britain and its universities.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-11-03T15:51:55.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626160/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/626160/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-31","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what representations he has received from the governments of other EU member states on the status of students after the 2018-19 academic year; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","51220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627329","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-03","<p>The UK currently sources only a small proportion of its food from developing countries. The most important drivers of retail food price inflation, including for products sourced from developing countries, are commodity prices, exchange rates and oil prices.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-03T11:28:45.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627329/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/627329/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-31","Food: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on food prices for products sourced from developing countries.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","907069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628054","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>I announced a review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures on 24 October. This will include a close look at Fixed Odds Betting Terminals.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-03T16:29:52.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628054/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628054/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress her Department has made on its commitment to end unsupervised high-stakes gambling on fixed odds betting terminals.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","907014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628055","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p><strong>The Government, together with the Local Government Association, set up the Leadership for Libraries Taskforce in 2015. The Taskforce has already published Toolkits and case studies to assist local authorities. We have also been developing, with the Taskforce, a draft vision and action plan for public libraries in England and this will be published shortly.</strong></p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-03T14:35:04.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628055/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628055/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to support library provision.","false","Biography information for Mike Wood","Dudley South","Mike Wood","907016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628056","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>Revenue from the soft drinks levy will be used to improve school sport and to get more children and young people involved in sport and physical activity.</p><p> </p><p>It will be used to double the PE and School Sport Premium, providing £320 million from September 2017 to all primary schools, to improve provision of PE and sport for all.</p><p> </p><p>Schools can decide how best to use this funding, and may choose to run extra-curricular activities during school holidays or to buy equipment.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-03T12:48:59.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628056/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628056/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if the Government will fund accessible physical activity sessions during school holidays from the proceeds of the soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","907011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628057","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>Improving access to culture for young people from low-income backgrounds remains a core part of this Government's strategy and our Culture White Paper.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is improving cultural access through a number of schemes including:</p><p> </p><ul><li>the Cultural Citizens Programme;</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>sustained investment in music and cultural education; and</li></ul><p> </p><p>through the Arts Council's Creative People and Places Programme.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-03T16:17:49.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628057/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628057/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Arts: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent steps she has taken to improve access to cultural experiences for young people from low-income households; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","907010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628058","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>Over 4 million homes and businesses now have access to superfast broadband as a direct result of the government’s programme; and We are currently reinvesting project savings and take-up revenues to extend the reach of superfast broadband beyond 95%.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-03T16:20:45.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628058/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628058/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to ensure that all parts of the UK can access superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","907015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628059","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-03","<p>Government wants to ensure the best possible deal for Britain on leaving the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>The Creative Industries are one of the UK’s greatest success stories, contributing over £87 billion to the economy and over £19 billion in exports.</p><p> </p><p>We are working closely with the industry to assess both the possible impacts and opportunities that our departure presents.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-03T16:18:26.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628059/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628059/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-31","Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on the creative industries of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","907009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628060","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Government will work hard to get the best deal for Britain. The PM has made it clear that we want to maximise access to free trade to allow British companies to trade with the EU.</p><p>The deal we negotiate will be bespoke, and we will make the most of the opportunities that our departure presents to do business right across the globe.</p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox",,"2016-11-03T15:59:29.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628060/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628060/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the potential cost to businesses of no longer having access to tariff-free trade with other EU Member States.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","907077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628061","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-03","<p>Increasing food and farming exports is a priority, with products sold in over 200 countries around the world and we are ambitious to do more. My Department is leading 12 food and agricultural technology export campaigns covering 24 key markets We have just launched our International Food and Drink Action Plan setting out how Government and industry will work together to increase exports even further.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-03T15:32:18.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628061/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628061/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Agricultural Products: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to increase food and farming exports.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","907071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628062","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-03","<p>The pharmaceutical sector is strategically important for the United Kingdom and we are having an active and ongoing dialogue with industry. We want the best possible arrangements for trade in all goods and services with the EU, including the pharmaceutical sector.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-11-03T15:44:30.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628062/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628062/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Drugs: UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of different possible trading arrangements with the EU for pharmaceuticals exports after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","907073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628063","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-03","<p>We are working closely with both the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and the Department for Exiting the EU to ensure that we obtain the best possible arrangements for our agricultural trade both with the EU and the rest of the world. We are not going to give a running commentary on those discussions at this stage.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-11-03T15:52:19.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628063/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/628063/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-31","Agricultural Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on the potential effect of trade tariffs on agricultural products on the agriculture industry after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","907075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623394","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-02","<p>Since the launch of the world's first social impact bond (SIB) in Peterborough Prison in 2010, the government has supported the development of 32 SIBs across the country. This includes 14 SIBs targeting youth unemployment, 7 SIBs focused upon homelessness and 11 SIBs centred on tackling a range of issues including mental health and employment, long term health conditions, children in care and loneliness amongst older people. We have also made more than £105m available over this Parliament to catalyse the growth of SIBs aimed at tackling a range of social issues.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-02T15:48:54.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623394/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623394/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-28","Social Impact Bonds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many and which social impact boards have been promoted by government departments since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","50912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623395","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>The introduction of the National Living Wage marked an important step towards building an economy that works for everyone. It ensures that low-wage workers are fairly rewarded for their contribution to a growing economy. At £7.20, it is a 50p increase on the National Minimum Wage and means a pay rise for over a million workers aged 25 and over across the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s assessment of the effects of the National Living Wage is contained within the published impact assessment, which is available at http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukdsi/2016/9780111141625/impacts/2016/3.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-02T17:10:05.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623395/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623395/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-28","Charities: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the national living wage on charities who are not subject to corporation tax in the (a) care home and (b) heritage sector.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","50913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623396","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-07","<p>At Budget 2016, the VAT registration threshold was increased so that businesses with a turnover of £83,000 and below do not have to register for VAT. This relieves many smaller businesses of the burdens associated with VAT.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-07T17:39:33.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623396/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623396/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623396/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-28","VAT: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of reducing the rate of VAT for small businesses.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","50899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623397","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-07","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will be preparing regional analysis of tax credits claims and Mandatory Reconsideration requests, and this will be available in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Concentrix workload is delegated by HMRC. The process for selecting claims for Concentrix compliance interventions is set out in sections A9 and A10 of the “specifications of requirement” annex of the Concentrix contract which can be found at: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/85d1b730-5e4e-4be8-ae4c-3ac1f359afc7</a></p><p> </p><p>At Budget 2016, the Government published the most recent policy costings. This can be found in section B23 at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf. However, this is in the process of being updated to reflect the change in circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Concentrix were most recently undertaking High Risk Renewals enquiries under section 18 of the Tax Credits Act 2002, under which the claimant needs to provide a declaration to show that they are entitled to receive tax credits. In these cases, the tax credits legislation places the onus on a claimant for ensuring that HMRC has the relevant information.</p><p>HMRC uses a wide range of data including third party data as part of a wider strategy to tackle tax credits error and fraud‎. HMRC has successfully reduced tax credits error and fraud from 8.1% in 2010-11 to 4.8% in 2014-15</p><p> </p><p>Where a discrepancy is detected, claimants are given 30 days to contact HMRC or provide the relevant information about their circumstances or household before making any decisions about their award. If after 30 days HMRC has had no contact, tax credit payments are either suspended or reduced. Often, claimants are required to submit information that had originally been requested as part of a Mandatory Reconsideration.</p><p>As announced on 7th October, the National Audit Office will also be conducting an investigation into HMRC’s contract with Concentrix.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50949 ; 50950 ; 50951 ; 50952 ; 50953 ; 50954 ; 50955 ; 50956","2016-11-07T17:49:02.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623397/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/623397/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-28","Concentrix: Garston and Halewood","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people in Garston and Halewood constituency have had a tax credit claim stopped by Concentrix.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","50948"
