"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622451","Home Office","false","2016-11-15","<p>In response to the French Government’s decision to close the camp in Calais, we have transferred over 200 asylum-seeking children to the UK, and we plan to transfer several hundred more children over the coming days and weeks.</p><p>Between 1 January and 1 October, over 140 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children in Europe were accepted for transfer to the UK under the family reunion provisions of the Dublin Regulation, of which over 80 are from France. This is in addition to our efforts in Calais.</p><p>Almost 3,000 people have been granted humanitarian protection under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme since it began. In the year ending June 2016, almost 50% of those were children.</p><p>There were 3,472 asylum claims from unaccompanied asylum seeking children in the year ending June 2016, a 54% rise compared to the year ending June 2015.</p><p>We continue to consult with every part of the UK including the devolved administrations, to encourage local authorities across the country to accept unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children under the National Transfer Scheme.</p><p>In July 2016, we increased the national rate of funding to local authorities taking responsibility for unaccompanied asylum seeking children; from £34,675 to £41,610 a year for those aged under 16 and from £25,915 to £33,215 a year for those aged 16 or 17. These rates were set following analysis of the costs of providing support to the two age groups based on financial information supplied by local authorities. We will keep these arrangements under review.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2769 ; HL2770 ; HL2771 ; HL2773","2016-11-15T14:50:03.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622451/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622451/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government to what extent the devolved administrations of the UK have been consulted on the plans for acceptance of unaccompanied child refugees.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL2772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622452","Home Office","false","2016-11-15","<p>In response to the French Government’s decision to close the camp in Calais, we have transferred over 200 asylum-seeking children to the UK, and we plan to transfer several hundred more children over the coming days and weeks.</p><p>Between 1 January and 1 October, over 140 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children in Europe were accepted for transfer to the UK under the family reunion provisions of the Dublin Regulation, of which over 80 are from France. This is in addition to our efforts in Calais.</p><p>Almost 3,000 people have been granted humanitarian protection under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme since it began. In the year ending June 2016, almost 50% of those were children.</p><p>There were 3,472 asylum claims from unaccompanied asylum seeking children in the year ending June 2016, a 54% rise compared to the year ending June 2015.</p><p>We continue to consult with every part of the UK including the devolved administrations, to encourage local authorities across the country to accept unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children under the National Transfer Scheme.</p><p>In July 2016, we increased the national rate of funding to local authorities taking responsibility for unaccompanied asylum seeking children; from £34,675 to £41,610 a year for those aged under 16 and from £25,915 to £33,215 a year for those aged 16 or 17. These rates were set following analysis of the costs of providing support to the two age groups based on financial information supplied by local authorities. We will keep these arrangements under review.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL2769 ; HL2770 ; HL2771 ; HL2772","2016-11-15T14:50:03.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622452/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622452/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the cost of accepting unaccompanied child refugees into the UK to date; and what provision has been made to meet the cost of an increase in the number of qualified children being accepted into the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Eames",,"Lord Eames","HL2773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622453","Home Office","false","2016-11-11","<p>The Home Office works closely with COMPASS providers and local authorities through Strategic Migration Partnerships to ensure the impacts of dispersal on local communities and services are considered when allocating accommodation to asylum seekers.</p><p>Local authorities and statutory bodies are consulted prior to the proposed use of all new asylum accommodation. However, in accordance with data protection principles, the identity of individual applicants is not routinely shared.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-11T14:51:23.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622453/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622453/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Compass Contracts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether local authorities are informed of the identity and location of asylum seekers who are housed on behalf of the Home Office in their area.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622454","Home Office","false","2016-11-17","<p>The Government provides funding to local authorities for accommodation to be provided to refugees resettled in the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme.</p><p>This covers the provision of food storage, cooking and washing facilities. We do not collect information on equipment such as television sets.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-17T15:58:22.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622454/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622454/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether accommodation provided for refugee families settled directly from Syria is equipped with television sets and access to UK channels.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622455","Home Office","false","2016-11-24","<p>Prevent is a key part of the UK’s counter-terrorism strategy (CONTEST). It safeguards and supports vulnerable individuals to stop them becoming terrorists or supporting terrorism. Prevent is working and works best when delivered in partnership with communities, civil society groups and individuals.</p><p>We work with a wide range of organisations to prevent people from becoming radicalised. These are organisations prepared to show leadership, point to solutions and challenge and confront terrorist and extremist ideologies whatever form they take.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-24T13:48:47.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622455/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622455/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Radicalism: Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had, or plan to have, with the Muslim Council of Britain on achieving a common strategy to combat the radicalisation of young people.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622456","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-09","<p>Common law tenancies in the private rented sector in England account for a small part of the housing market, mainly where the rent payable is high or the landlord lives in the property. The default tenancy is assured short hold, with 81 per cent of the 4.3 million household in the private rented sector occupying under such tenancies. The Government is not aware of misuse of common law tenancies to avoid statutory protections. In particular the provisions in the Housing Act 2004 relating to Houses in Multiple Occupation, including mandatory licensing, apply to properties occupied by common law tenancies.</p><p>In October 2010 changes were introduced to assured tenancy rules by increasing the rent limit so tenancies with rents not exceeding £100,000 are no longer common law tenancies. The Government has no plans to make any further changes to the laws applying to common law tenancies.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-11-09T14:21:09.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622456/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622456/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-27","Private Rented Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they consider that common law tenancies for (1) residential accommodation in general, and (2) houses in multiple occupation in particular, are being misused, and if so whether changes are needed to tenancy laws.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622457","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-09","<p>There are an estimated 4.3 million households in the private rented sector in England. The majority, 85 per cent, are statutorily protected tenancies (assured, assured short hold and regulated tenancies). The Government has not made any estimate of how many of the remaining 15 per cent (which includes tenancies and licences granted by resident landlords, educational establishments and others) are common law tenancies.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-11-09T14:20:38.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622457/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622457/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-27","Private Rented Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have made an assessment of the use of common law tenancies for the provision of housing accommodation and what is their estimate of the number of common law tenancies used for the provision of housing accommodation.","false","Biography information for Lord Greaves",,"Lord Greaves","HL2778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622458","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>All public appointments are made on merit and follow a recruitment process regulated by the Commissioner for Public Appointments.</p><p>The Commissioner collects and publishes data on an annual basis relating to public appointments within his regulatory remit including political activity.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-11-07T17:32:45.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622458/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622458/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-27","Public Appointments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure political impartiality in the public appointments process.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL2779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622459","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-09","​In June 2016 the Human Rights Council published a report detailing the horrific extent of trafficking of Yezidi women within Iraq and Syria. We do not have any evidence to suggest that Yezidi women are being trafficked outside of Iraq and Syria. We continue to work closely with our Global Coalition partners to defeat Daesh, including those in the region.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-09T15:27:24.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622459/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622459/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-27","Islamic State: Yazidis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the extent of the trafficking of Yazidi women by Daesh in Iraq and Syria; what countries have been identified as their destination; and what representations they have made to the governments of those countries in relation to identifying and assisting any such women and girls.","true","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL2780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622460","Home Office","false","2016-11-11","<p>Eligibility for the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement programme (VPR) is based on established vulnerability criteria used by the UNHCR, which includes those who have been victims of sexual violence and torture.</p><p>Whilst the VPR is limited to Syrian nationals, the UK operates a number of other resettlement schemes which are open to all nationalities. This includes our long-running Gateway and Mandate schemes and our new Vulnerable Children’s Resettlement scheme. In the year ending June 2016, the UK resettled over 100 Iraqis under the Gateway and Mandate schemes.</p><p>The UK continues to support humanitarian efforts by providing £79.5 million to help the three million Iraqis who have been displaced, and over eight million people in need, many of whom have been victims of Daesh’s abuses and persecution.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-11T14:55:52.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622460/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622460/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the Syrian vulnerable person resettlement programme should be expanded to include victims of sexual violence and torture by Daesh and other armed groups in Iraq.","true","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL2781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622461","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-07","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer given by my hon. Friend, the Minister for Defence Procurement (Harriett Baldwin), in the House of Commons on 17 October 2016 to Question 48369.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-11-07T17:11:09.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622461/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622461/answer","Hansard Extract  17 October 2016,  48369.docx"," Ministry of Defence Procurement","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622461/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-27","Defence: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether measures are in place to protect Ministry of Defence procurement budgets from the fall in the value of sterling against the US dollar and the Euro; and if so, what those measures are.","false","Biography information for Lord Hutton of Furness",,"Lord Hutton of Furness","HL2782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622462","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-09","<p>Following an open competition a contract to recycle the vessel was awarded to Leyal Ship Recycling Ltd on 23 August 2016. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) subsequently received an outline proposal from a business consortium to purchase the former HMS ILLUSTRIOUS as a heritage asset. However, it has not been taken forward.</p><p> </p><p>HMS ILLUSTRIOUS is now the property of Leyal Ship Recycling Ltd and to cancel the sale agreement at this late stage would result in significant financial cost to the MOD.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-11-09T15:24:34.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622462/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622462/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-27","HMS Illustrious","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the willingness of a group of investors to purchase and refurbish HMS Illustrious so that it can become a museum in the UK, whether they will now suspend the sale and removal of the ship so that it is not broken up for scrap and instead, in keeping with the Government statement of September 2012, "preserved intact as a lasting tribute to service personnel who served" on HMS Illustrious, HMS Invincible and HMS Ark Royal.","false","Biography information for Lord Kinnock",,"Lord Kinnock","HL2783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622463","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is currently reviewing its trade policy as the UK prepares to leave the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate and design, in time, our own trade arrangements, including with our 52 Commonwealth partners. We recognise the need for a smooth transition which minimises disruption to our trading relationship with the Carribean.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-11-01T15:27:43.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622463/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622463/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-27","Overseas Trade: Caribbean","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to maintain, or improve, Commonwealth Caribbean trade with, and preferential access to, the UK market, particularly in relation to commodities such as bananas and sugar, after the UK leaves the EU; and if so, how that will be achieved.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL2784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622464","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-09","<p>The UK remains committed to being a world leader in free trade, working with a range of partners to strengthen our economic ties. We recognise the need for a smooth transition which minimises disruption to our trading relationships. We are considering the options for this and will of course work with our EU and international partners in taking it forward. We are taking advantage of all the opportunities available to us to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-11-09T15:25:06.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622464/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622464/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-27","Overseas Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the UK will still be able to trade under the existing EU free trade agreements once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL2785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622465","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>Having a skilled workforce in place, attracting new talent and ensuring there are opportunities to enter and progress through the farming sector is vital for the future of UK food and farming. The Government recognises there are barriers facing young new entrants to get started in farming including the high cost of land and access to finance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is exploring the range of different farm business models that can open up opportunities for new entrants such as agricultural tenancies, share-farming, contract farming, franchise farming and joint ventures. These business models can provide young new farmers with an opportunity to gain experience and build up capital to progress their careers in farming.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is currently providing additional support for young new entrants into farming through the EU Basic Payment Scheme where eligible farmers aged between 18 and 40 can claim a 25% uplift on up to 90 hectares of their Basic Payment Scheme payments for up to five years after they have started in business.</p><p> </p><p>Support is also provided through EU Rural Development Programme schemes including the Growth Programme and LEADER providing help for rural entrepreneurs including farmers setting up a new business or expanding or improving an existing business. In addition the Countryside Productivity scheme provides support to help increase productivity and enhance the competitiveness of farming and forestry industries. Defra also provides grant support to the National Federation of Young Farmers Clubs to provide training opportunities for young farmers and we are working with the Food and Drink Federation to treble the number of apprenticeships across the sector.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the UK is a member of the EU these funding streams will remain in place and Defra continues to engage with young farmers to help shape our future plans for UK agricultural policy outside of the EU.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2787","2016-11-10T16:20:34.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622465/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622465/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622465/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Farmers: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to support young farmers to stay in farming and to encourage new entrants to become farmers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL2786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622466","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>Having a skilled workforce in place, attracting new talent and ensuring there are opportunities to enter and progress through the farming sector is vital for the future of UK food and farming. The Government recognises there are barriers facing young new entrants to get started in farming including the high cost of land and access to finance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is exploring the range of different farm business models that can open up opportunities for new entrants such as agricultural tenancies, share-farming, contract farming, franchise farming and joint ventures. These business models can provide young new farmers with an opportunity to gain experience and build up capital to progress their careers in farming.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is currently providing additional support for young new entrants into farming through the EU Basic Payment Scheme where eligible farmers aged between 18 and 40 can claim a 25% uplift on up to 90 hectares of their Basic Payment Scheme payments for up to five years after they have started in business.</p><p> </p><p>Support is also provided through EU Rural Development Programme schemes including the Growth Programme and LEADER providing help for rural entrepreneurs including farmers setting up a new business or expanding or improving an existing business. In addition the Countryside Productivity scheme provides support to help increase productivity and enhance the competitiveness of farming and forestry industries. Defra also provides grant support to the National Federation of Young Farmers Clubs to provide training opportunities for young farmers and we are working with the Food and Drink Federation to treble the number of apprenticeships across the sector.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the UK is a member of the EU these funding streams will remain in place and Defra continues to engage with young farmers to help shape our future plans for UK agricultural policy outside of the EU.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL2786","2016-11-10T16:20:34.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622466/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622466/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Farmers: Recruitment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what they have identified as the main barriers to young entrants hoping to become farmers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL2787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622467","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>There are currently no plans to introduce a subsidy ceiling on farm payments. Previously, the Government has opposed the European Commission’s proposals for capping farm payments due to the risk that to do so would simply encourage farms to restructure into smaller, and perhaps, less efficient units to avoid losing out on payments.</p><p> </p><p>However, the government is looking at how best to support farming and the countryside after we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-10T12:30:24.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622467/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622467/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622467/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Agriculture: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to introduce a subsidy ceiling on farm payments; and if so, what ceiling.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL2788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622468","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Department has not made a direct comparative assessment of the animal welfare, environmental and human health benefits of grass-fed against grain-fed diets, although we are aware of various research reports and industry initiatives which support the view that grass feeding can have benefits for animal welfare and the environment, and play a part in determining meat quality.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-10T12:30:47.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622468/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622468/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Livestock: Animal Feed","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have made a comparative assessment of the animal welfare, environmental and human health benefits of pasture-fed livestock, against livestock raised on a primarily grain-based diet.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL2789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622469","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>There is no legal definition of “grass-fed“ in relation to livestock rearing practice, although there is a general obligation in food labelling and consumer law that food labelling should not mislead the consumer and this obligation remains in place. Previous voluntary labelling guidance defined grass-fed as “fed primarily on grass in the field”.</p><p> </p><p>Defra is currently working on a range of proposals to inform discussions about the shape of a future agriculture policy and we want to ensure that the future regulatory framework continues to provide consumers with confidence in the food that they are buying, and continues to secure our world-leading reputation for high quality and standards.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-10T12:31:27.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622469/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622469/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Livestock: Animal Feed","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will develop guidance on the use of the term "grass-fed" for livestock so that consumers can make more informed decisions when buying meat and dairy products.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL2790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622470","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Government publication Agriculture in the United Kingdom 2015 shows that the median age of farm holders in the UK is 59.</p><p> </p><p>Having a skilled workforce in place, attracting new talent and ensuring that there are opportunities to enter and progress through the farming sector is vital for the future of UK food and farming. The Government is aware of concerns about the aging profile of farming and recognises the challenges facing young new entrants to farming including the high cost of land and access to finance.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is keen to work with industry to explore and promote a range of different farm business models where established farmers can open up opportunities to the next generation of young farmers to gain a foothold and experience in the sector such as agricultural tenancies, share-farming, contract farming, franchise farming and joint ventures.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-10T12:24:58.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622470/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622470/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Farmers: Age","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the average age of farmers in England; and what assessment they have made of the impact of farmers' ages on the future of English farming.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL2791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622471","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-08","<p>The compensation figures for all Train Operating Companies operating Delay Repay covering the years 2009-10 to 2014-15 are published on the GOV.UK website, and a copy of the full figures is provided in the attached document. Overall figures are below. Figures for the 2015-16 financial year for all Train Operating Companies are expected to be published on the GOV.UK website later this year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Amounts in £ (000s)</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2014-15 - 25,623</p><p>2013-14 - 22,608</p><p>2012-13- 12,603</p><p>2011-12 - 8,021</p><p>2010-11 - 3,256</p><p>2009 -10 - 2,981</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-08T13:38:22.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622471/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622471/answer","HL2792 - toc-compensation-2009-2015.pdf","TOC - Compensation 2009/10-2014/5","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622471/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-27","Railways: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much compensation was paid to passengers for delays and cancellations by each train operating company during the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622472","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Department for Transport has not made an estimate of unclaimed compensation. The Office of Rail and Road considered this issue in its response to the Which? super-complaint on passenger compensation and has committed to working with the industry to agree a set of indicators that will show how the take-up of compensation is changing over time.</p><p> </p><p>We are also working with the industry as it develops improvements to make the compensation process as easy for passengers as possible, including further automation. A number of train companies have already introduced fully automated compensation and other are planning to do so.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-07T13:44:44.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622472/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622472/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-27","Railways: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the amount of compensation due to passengers for delays and cancellations which was unclaimed from each train operating company during the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622473","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Rail Delivery Group (RDG) is leading the industry’s response to the Office of Rail and Road’s recommendations following the Which? super-complaint, and we are discussing this with them as they lead efforts to raise standards.</p><p> </p><p>Actions already taken by the RDG include:</p><p> </p><ul><li>the launch of a coordinated rail industry communications campaign to raise customer awareness of their right to and how to claim compensation; and</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>an update to the National Rail Enquiries website to direct customers from the front page to full details about compensation and links to claim forms and specific information for every train company</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport requires bidders for new franchises to put forward proposals to make the compensation process swift and simple.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-07T13:44:13.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622473/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622473/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-27","Railways: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proposals they have made to, or discussed with, train operating companies to simplify procedures for passengers to claim compensation for delays and cancellations.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622474","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-07","<p>On 13 October 2016 the Secretary of State for Transport announced an improved compensation scheme for passengers if their train is more than 15 minutes late. We will implement the policy in the Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) franchise, which includes Southern, within months. Following its introduction on GTR services, ‘Delay Repay 15’ will then be rolled out across the network starting with the new South Western, West Midlands and South Eastern franchises. All franchise competitions let by the Department for Transport (DfT) will include requirements to introduce this policy and the DfT is exploring opportunities to roll this out for all DfT franchises during this Parliament.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-07T13:43:23.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622474/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622474/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-27","Railways: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect each train operating company to implement passenger compensation for delays of 15 minutes or more.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622475","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Government has taken decisive steps to ensure that asset managers pay their fair share of tax. In Summer Budget 2015, the Government closed loopholes to ensure that asset managers pay the right amount of Capital Gains Tax on their carried interest.</p><p> </p><p>Legislation in the Finance Act 2016 ensures that this carried interest remains subject to a Capital Gains Tax rate of 28% for higher and additional rate tax payers, despite the cut in the main rate of Capital Gains Tax to 20%.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, legislation in the Finance Act 2016 ensures that asset managers engaged in short-term trading activity are subject to income tax on the carried interest they receive, rather than Capital Gains Tax.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-11-10T12:24:20.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622475/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622475/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Private Equity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to review the tax benefits extended to private equity partners by the application of a special rate to carried interest income.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622476","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-08","<p>The provision of the school crossing patrol service is a matter for the local authority. Legislation gives ‘Appropriate Authorities’ the power to make arrangements (for example with schools and other bodies) for the patrolling of places where children cross roads on their way to or from school, but does not impose a duty on them to do so. The legislation defines Appropriate Authorities outside Greater London as the council of the county, unitary authority or metropolitan district; there are slightly different arrangements in London and in Scotland.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-08T15:43:25.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622476/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622476/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-27","Pedestrian Crossings: Schools","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether section 26 of the Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984 (as amended) permits school crossing patrols to be appointed and operated by schools or bodies other than the local authority.","false","Biography information for Baroness Pinnock",,"Baroness Pinnock","HL2797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622477","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>Academies and free schools have powers in their funding agreements to pay for school crossing patrols, if they choose to do so. The model funding agreement provides that an Academy Trust can spend General Annual Grant on the normal running costs of the academy, this can include spending on school crossing patrols.</p><p> </p><p>Under section 50 of the School Standards and Framework Act 1998, local authority maintained schools can also undertake lawful activity that is for the purpose of the school, including paying for school crossing patrols. Independent schools are private bodies and can also fund school crossing patrols.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-08T14:55:01.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622477/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622477/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-27","Schools: Pedestrian Crossings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether (1) academies, (2) free schools and (3) independent schools have powers to fund the cost of school crossing patrols.","false","Biography information for Baroness Pinnock",,"Baroness Pinnock","HL2798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622478","Department for Education","false","2016-11-08","<p>As spending on school crossing patrols is classified, for accounting purposes, as local transport spending rather than education services, it would not be appropriate to include school crossing patrols in the School and Early Years Finance (England) Regulations 2013 to enable such patrols to be funded from local authority schools or non-schools education budgets.</p><p> </p><p>However, local authorities are able to fund school crossing patrols from other non-ring fenced resources such as council tax and business rate income made available through the local government finance settlement. Additionally, there is nothing to stop schools using their delegated budgets to fund a service that is not strictly educational but clearly in the interest of the school, such as health services, transport or crossing patrols.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-08T14:54:27.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622478/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622478/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-27","Schools: Pedestrian Crossings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether consideration has been given to amending the regulations in the School and Early Years Finance (England) Regulations 2013 which specifically exclude the use of a local authority’s non-schools education budget for funding school crossing patrols.","false","Biography information for Baroness Pinnock",,"Baroness Pinnock","HL2799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622479","Department of Health","false","2016-11-08","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer I gave on 3 November 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2016-10-20/HL2508/" target="_blank">HL2508</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Government welcomed the independent taskforce’s recommendations for mental health and fully endorses the report. We continue to work across Government departments to progress taking the taskforce recommendations forward.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-11-08T15:14:39.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622479/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622479/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the publication in July of <i>Implementing the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health</i>, whether they intend to publish a national Mental Health Strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL2800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622480","Department of Health","false","2016-11-08","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer I gave on 3 November 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2016-10-20/HL2509/" target="_blank">HL2509</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains committed to achieving parity of esteem for mental and physical health. The Government welcomed the publication of the <em>Five Year Forward View for Mental Health</em> and <em>Future in Mind: Promoting, protecting and improving our children and young people’s mental health and wellbeing</em> to transform mental health services by 2020, which is a significant step forward in achieving parity of esteem between mental and physical health. We continue to work with NHS England and other arm’s length bodies to embed the recommendations set out in these reports into our national policies and we are committed to reporting regularly and transparently on our progress.</p><p> </p><p>We will be holding NHS England to account through the NHS Mandate to ensure that we deliver the commitments set out in these reports.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-11-08T15:14:11.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622480/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622480/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made on creating parity of esteem between mental and physical health; and how they are currently measuring this.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL2801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622481","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-09","<p>The Government estimates that a further 3 million British citizens resident overseas would be enfranchised by the 'votes for life' proposals set out in the policy statement published on 7 October.</p><p>The policy statement also sets out how applicants will be required to establish a connection to a UK address. For those whose previous registration cannot be verified, or who were not previously registered, documentary evidence or an attestation can be used. The additional costs will be highly dependent upon the number of eligible electors who apply to vote and to renew their registrations.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-11-09T16:17:15.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622481/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622481/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-27","Electoral Register: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of British citizens living overseas who may be entitled to qualify for inclusion on UK electoral registers if the current 15 year time limit is abolished; how they intend to ensure that it will be possible to check previous residency or inclusion against previous electoral registers given that those registers may no longer exist; and what estimate they have made of the cost to local authorities of conducting such a process.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL2802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622482","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>As stated in my previous answer to HL 2496, the Government is currently conducting a “discovery phase” in relation to understanding the issue of duplicate applications. It is right that we will need to meet the needs both of citizens and administrators when considering the right way forward. In discussions with administrators and others to date, it has become clear there are wide-ranging views on whether citizens would use a look-up tool in practice. There are also wide-ranging views on the kind of intervention that would most benefit administrators. That is why our evidence-gathering phase is so important. This discovery phase is also important for us to understand the practical considerations of the different possible solutions.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-11-08T16:33:10.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622482/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622482/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-27","Electoral Register: Internet","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen on 26 October (HL2496) concerning progress in assessing the benefits of an online registration checking tool, what assessment they have made of (1) the extent to which an online registration checking tool could increase electoral registration levels by enabling people to check whether or not they are already registered before attempting to register online, and (2) the amount of time election administration staff would spend checking for duplicate registrations; and how they intend to take into consideration the relative importance of each of those benefits when assessing options.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL2803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622483","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>‘Transforming our Justice System’ sets out the Government’s plans to modernise the justice system and it consults on specific elements of these reform proposals. This includes certain issues that are relevant to the tribunals, such as tribunal panel composition and the provision of ‘assisted digital’ services.</p><p><br> As the noble Lady will be aware, the consultation is available to the public, and anyone with an interest is welcome to feed in their views. Ministry of Justice and HMCTS have engaged directly with the judiciary, who are fundamental to the success of reform, in considering the operational implications of the reform proposals. They have also engaged and worked with other relevant Government departments, key legal institutions, and a range of stakeholders with an interest in disability and mental health. These discussions are ongoing and will continue as the plans are further developed and implemented.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-11-09T15:29:07.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622483/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622483/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Tribunals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Keen of Elie on 17 October (HL2078), which stakeholders, including disability groups, officials are engaging with, and on what relevant matters, in the consultation on the tribunal system <i>Transforming our Justice System</i>.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL2804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622484","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>We have not made any representations to the Israeli authorities over this specific issue. The UK Government continues to argue for a just outcome for all the people affected by illegal settlement construction and the confiscation of land due to the Separation Barrier.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-04T12:20:21.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622484/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622484/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-27","Occupied Territories: Land","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made, or intend to make, to the government of Israel about reports of 1,500 dunams of Palestinian land being illegally cultivated by Israelis from the moshav of Mateh Yehuda near Latrun and the settlement of Mevo Horon.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622485","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-07","<p>Before we consider an extension of the Groceries Code Adjudicator’s (GCA) remit, we need to be absolutely clear on where any problems exist in the supply chain – and that an extended remit is the right response to those problems. Therefore, it is important that we hear views from all parties in the UK’s grocery supply chain.</p><p> </p><p>In order to gather these views we recently launched a Call for Evidence seeking views on the remit of the GCA.</p><p> </p><p>The Call for Evidence launched on the 17 October and closes on the 10 January.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-11-07T16:10:58.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622485/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622485/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-27","Groceries Code Adjudicator","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to extend the remit of the Groceries Code Adjudicator.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622486","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>Supporting our farmers and protecting the environment will form an important part of our exit from the EU. We are now focused on making sure that all our policies are delivering for the UK and to grow our world-leading food and farming industry.</p><p> </p><p>We regularly meet farmers and industry representatives and are well aware of the challenges farmers face as their need for workers fluctuates depending on the season and the state of the crop.</p><p> </p><p>With regard to seasonal labour, until we leave the EU, there are no changes to labour movements. Defra is very aware that migrant workers from other EU countries will be one of the complex issues that will have to be resolved as part of our exit negotiation and future relationship with the EU. We are currently working with colleagues across government to understand the issues and explore options.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-10T12:23:28.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622486/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622486/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the demand for seasonal workers in the agricultural industry to ensure crops are harvested in the required timescales.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622487","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>We welcome Professor Graham Seymour’s research project and my officials will be writing to him shortly to invite him to present his results to them.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-10T16:19:38.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622487/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622487/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Tomatoes: Research","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the research by Professor Graham Seymour into controlling the softening of the tomato fruit.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622488","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>The UK contributes statistical data to the European Commission cereals harvest forecast, which is reviewed each month. The EU forecast for 2016/17, as at the end of October, indicates total cereals availability of 294.8 million tonnes. This represents a 5.4% reduction on 2015/16. EU harvest forecasts are published on the Commission’s website.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-10T12:25:44.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622488/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622488/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Cereals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the harvest forecast for arable crops across the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622489","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Government is aware that a high level of erucic acid has been detected in some oilseed rape deliveries to crushing plants over the past year. The Government is working with the industry to understand the cause of the problem. A survey is being carried out by the supply chain to capture data on the seed used as well as the crop production, harvest and storage methods. This information will be independently analysed by the Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board.</p><p> </p><p>Maximum permitted levels for erucic acid in products entering the food chain are set under EU Commission Regulation No 1881/2006 (as amended) setting maximum levels for certain contaminants in foodstuffs. Local authority enforcement officers undertake routine monitoring to check compliance with the legislation.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-11-10T12:26:22.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622489/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622489/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-27","Oilseed Rape","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of erucic acid contamination of oilseed rape.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622490","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-08","<p>Vehicle operators, contractors and farmers who deposit mud on the road are potentially liable for a range of offences as set out in the Highways Act 1980 (as amended) and the Road Traffic Act 1988.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the Department for Transport does not provide specific advice to farmers, the National Farmers Union provides advice in respect to mud on the road to their members through their website.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-08T15:40:56.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622490/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622490/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-27","Agricultural Machinery: Roads","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what advice they are giving to farmers to reduce the number of incidents of mud getting onto the roads.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL2811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622491","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-11","<p>The Charity Commission has an ongoing statutory inquiry into Kids Company and will publish a report once its investigation has concluded.</p><p> </p><p>The Metropolitan Police Service announced that it had discontinued its investigation into Kids Company in January 2016.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-11-11T10:56:17.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622491/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622491/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Kids Company","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect the investigations into Kids Company by the Metropolitan Police and the Charity Commission to conclude and when they expect those bodies to report their findings.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL2812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622492","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Official Receiver sent a report regarding the winding up of Keeping Kids Company to creditors, including Cabinet Office and HMRC, on 1 October 2015. The Official Receiver’s enquiries into the affairs of Keeping Kids Company are continuing, and it would not be appropriate for me to comment on an ongoing investigation.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-11-07T16:11:25.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622492/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622492/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-27","Kids Company","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to receive a report of the Official Receiver's winding up of Kids Company.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL2813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622494","Attorney General","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Law Officers’ Departments have not procured any steel in the last 12 months.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-11-04T18:58:31.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622494/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622494/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-27","Attorney General: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent estimate he has made of the level of procurement of British steel by the Law Officers' Departments in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622495","Attorney General","false","2016-11-04","<p>In light of the Government’s manifesto commitment to achieve three million new apprenticeship starts in England by the end of the Parliament, the Cabinet Office will be centrally collecting data on apprenticeships to allow the Civil Service to report on its contribution towards the national target.</p><p> </p><p>Crown Prosecution Service employed 491apprentices, 194 apprentices have secured a permanent post prior to the 2016 intake of Apprentices.</p><p> </p><p>Serious Fraud Office employed 19 apprentices, 12 apprentices have secured a permanent post.</p><p> </p><p>Government Legal Department employed 9 apprentices; all have been or will be offered a permanent post.</p><p> </p><p>Attorney General’s Office and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecutions Inspectorate have had no apprentices over this time.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>LOD</p></td><td><p>LOCATION</p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="17"><p><strong>CPS</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>CASEWORK DIVISIONS</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>EAST MIDLANDS</strong></p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>MERSEY CHESHIRE</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>NORTH EAST</strong></p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>NORTH WEST</strong></p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>SOUTH EAST</strong></p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><