strong>CENTRAL LONDON</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>4*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>5*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>7*</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br>*N.B. Serious Fraud Office has calculated this by financial year as this is how their data is recorded.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-11-04T18:57:56.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622495/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622495/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-27","Attorney General: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many apprenticeships have been created in the Law Officers' Departments in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622496","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>The information is not centrally held in the form requested. Over the last year Government has acted to level the playing field for UK steel producers in light of the complex global challenges faced by the UK steel sector. Last December Government issued guidance to central government departments on how to ensure that they take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers when conducting their procurement activities. This guidance is also being extended to the wider public sector.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-04T09:50:39.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622496/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622496/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-27","Cabinet Office: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent estimate he has made of the level of procurement of British steel by his Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622497","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>The public sector exit payment cap will apply to exits specified in regulations that will be laid in Parliament and approved via the affirmative procedure. The cap will not apply to any exits that have occurred before the regulations have been laid and come into force.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-01T14:23:50.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622497/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622497/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Civil Servants: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 21 October 2016 to Question 48873, whether he plans to backdate the commencement date of secondary legislation to bring a £95,000 cap into force before 1 October 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","50658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622498","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>In March 2016 we published the refresh of our <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/510994/Talent_Action_Plan_2016.pdf" target="_blank">Talent Action Plan</a> setting out our commitment to ensure that the civil service becomes the most inclusive employer in the UK. We are taking forward a number of initiatives to attract and progress people from diverse background in our workforce. These include The Civil Service committing to deliver at least 30,000 apprenticeship starts in England by 2020<strong>, </strong>introducing name-blind sifting for job applications, and<strong> </strong>leading work with other employers to develop a common set of measures to understand socio-economic background in workforces and applicants for jobs. We will adopt the new measures, when developed, to better understand the socio-economic background of Fast Stream and Fast Track Apprentice scheme applicants.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-04T11:50:58.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622498/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622498/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-27","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department plans to change the way in which it measures the socio-economic background of (a) Fast Stream and (b) Fast Track apprentice scheme applicants.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","50777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622499","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Fast Stream selection process has been significantly re-designed in order to reduce the application to hire timeline, and also enhance the socio-economic diversity of those applying and selected. This re-design was introduced in September 2016. This year, we intend to decrease the length of time to offer to around 16 weeks (a reduction from between 18 – 31 weeks last year) for the majority of candidates and move to 12 weeks next year. This will allow us to gather sufficient applicant data to be confident of our assessment decision-making within the re-designed approach.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-04T11:47:55.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622499/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622499/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-27","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress he has made on re-designing the Fast Stream selection process to reduce its length from 18-31 weeks to 12 weeks.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","50778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622500","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>Since 2011, Cabinet Office has created 208 apprenticeships. Information on subsequently permanent employment in the Civil Service is not centrally held.</p><p>The table below provides a breakdown of the number of apprenticeships created in each financial year since 2011. The locations reflect the fact the Cabinet Office is primarily based in London.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of apprenticeships created</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Location</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>London</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>London</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>33</p></td><td><p>London (32) Liverpool (1)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>38</p></td><td><p>London</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>48</p></td><td><p>London (45) Norwich (1) Bristol (1) Liverpool (1)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>56*</p></td><td><p>London (54) Norwich (1) Liverpool (1)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Figure at end of October 2016</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-11-04T15:10:12.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622500/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622500/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-27","Cabinet Office: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many apprenticeships have been created in his Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622501","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will be preparing regional analysis of tax credits claims and mandatory reconsideration requests in due course.</p><p>As announced on 7th October, the National Audit Office will also be conducting an investigation into HMRC’s contract with Concentrix.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50719 ; 50720","2016-11-04T14:07:45.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622501/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622501/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will conduct a review of the effect of erroneous decisions by Concentrix on people in (a) Bristol West and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","50844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622502","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Department’s assessment as to whether the Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon can be considered to be value for money is currently underway. No assessment has been provided to the Hendry Review team.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-02T11:40:40.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622502/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622502/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-27","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the value for money case for Swansea Bay Tidal Lagoon; and whether that assessment  has been shared with the Hendy Review team.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","50847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622503","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-01","<p>Central to the Government’s long term economic plan is the creation of jobs and making work pay. We know that work is the best route out of poverty. Our welfare reforms are about reversing the trend of working age benefits rising faster than earnings since the recession to ensure it pays to work. They are focussed on supporting those people who can work to find and keep work rather than rely on benefits, ensuring fairness and affordability for the tax payer. We are committed to balancing incentivising work with protecting those who cannot work, and helping with the costs of additional needs. That is why benefits for the additional costs of disability, and for carers, are up-rated each year in line with prices.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-01T16:18:08.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622503/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622503/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-27","Social Security Benefits: Inflation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 1.137 of the Summer Budget 2015, if he will make an assessment of the effect of recent changes in the level of inflation on the proposed freeze of working age benefits.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","50697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622504","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will be preparing regional analysis of tax credits claims and mandatory reconsideration requests in due course.</p><p>As announced on 7th October, the National Audit Office will also be conducting an investigation into HMRC’s contract with Concentrix.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50720 ; 50844","2016-11-04T14:07:45.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622504/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622504/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Concentrix: Bristol West","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of tax credit cases awaiting consideration by Concentrix in Bristol West constituency.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","50719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622505","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) will be preparing regional analysis of tax credits claims and mandatory reconsideration requests in due course.</p><p>As announced on 7th October, the National Audit Office will also be conducting an investigation into HMRC’s contract with Concentrix.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","50719 ; 50844","2016-11-04T14:07:45.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622505/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622505/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Concentrix: Bristol West","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people in Bristol West constituency have had a tax credit claim stopped by Concentrix; and how many such people have subsequently had their claim reinstated by HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","50720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622506","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>As the Chancellor outlined at the Treasury Select Committee recently, the government is carrying out a range of analysis, which will help to inform the Prime Minister’s negotiating strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The government has provided a guarantee for all European structural and investment fund projects signed before the Autumn Statement. The government has also guaranteed all European structural projects signed after the Autumn Statement and before the UK’s departure from the European Union, provided that they pass the value-for-money test and are in line with domestic strategic priorities.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-04T14:25:37.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622506/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622506/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","EU Grants and Loans: Bristol","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment the Government has made of the effect on (a) Bristol West and (b) Bristol City Council area of the shortfall in funding from the European Regional Development Fund and European Social Fund after the 2014 to 2020 programme has ended.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","50723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622507","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>As the Chancellor outlined at the Treasury Select Committee recently, the government is carrying out a range of analysis, which will help to inform the Prime Minister’s negotiating strategy.</p><p> </p><p>The government has provided a guarantee for all European structural and investment fund projects signed before the Autumn Statement. The government has also guaranteed all European structural projects signed after the Autumn Statement and before the UK’s departure from the European Union, provided that they pass the value-for-money test and are in line with domestic strategic priorities.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-04T14:26:27.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622507/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622507/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Economic Situation: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government is conducting a regional assessment of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on (a) Bristol West, (b) Bristol City Council area and (c) the region covered by the Counties formerly known as Avon.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","50724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622508","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) ensures that High Net Worth Individuals pay the right amount of tax by applying the appropriate PAYE/NIC regulations correctly and by requiring them to declare the appropriate tax due through their personal tax return under the Self-Assessment system. This is monitored by HMRC’s “High Net Worth Unit”.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-04T14:10:18.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622508/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622508/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Football: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that high net worth footballers pay the correct amount of income tax.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","50728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622509","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet regularly with the Financial Conduct Authority to discuss relevant regulatory issues.</p><p> </p><p>As was the case with previous Administrations, it is not the Treasury's practice to provide details of all such discussions.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-03T15:31:09.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622509/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622509/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Wells Fargo","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Financial Conduct Authority on Wells Fargo bank.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","50756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622510","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-02","<p>As announced by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) in October, it has now received the final report from the appointed skilled person. It will consider the report’s findings along with all of the relevant material before making its findings publicly available.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-02T15:54:37.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622510/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622510/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects the review by the Financial Conduct Authority into the Royal Bank of Scotland's Global Restructuring Group to be published; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","50757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622511","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is preparing for the UK to make an orderly and successful exit from the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>As we have set out previously, the aggregate spending plans for this Parliament remain in place.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-01T14:25:02.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622511/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622511/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made an estimate of the potential effect on Total Managed Expenditure in 2017-18 of the UK's decision to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","50696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622512","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Department does not directly procure steel in the undertaking of its operations.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-04T13:24:24.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622512/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622512/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Treasury: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the level of procurement of British steel by his Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622513","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) recognises that this will be a difficult time for claimants. HMRC is therefore part of the “tell us once” service that allows people to report a death and inform a number of government services at one time rather than individually. When HMRC is informed of the death of a claimant it makes contact with any surviving partner to help them make a new claim, if they are entitled to it.</p><p> </p><p>Child Tax Credit claimants can have their claim backdated for up to 31 days. This includes those who are making a claim following a bereavement. There are no plans to change this.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-04T14:27:13.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622513/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622513/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Child Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to allow payments of child tax credits to bereaved partners to be backdated to the date of the death of their partner.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","50628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622514","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>Discussions are ongoing on all devolution issues across government and with local areas.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-01T12:44:44.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622514/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622514/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Combined Authorities: Borrowing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to give non-transport borrowing powers to combined authorities.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","50654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622515","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>Discussion are ongoing on all devolution issues across government and with local areas.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-01T12:42:57.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622515/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622515/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Combined Authorities: Borrowing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on giving non-transport borrowing powers to combined authorities.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","50655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622516","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>HM Treasury regularly reviews the impacts of all taxes. The initial Tax Information and Impact Note is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/stamp-duty-land-tax-higher-rates-on-purchases-of-additional-residential-properties/stamp-duty-land-tax-higher-rates-on-purchases-of-additional-residential-properties" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/stamp-duty-land-tax-higher-rates-on-purchases-of-additional-residential-properties/stamp-duty-land-tax-higher-rates-on-purchases-of-additional-residential-properties</a></p><p> </p><p>Any changes would be made at fiscal events in the normal way.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-01T16:33:56.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622516/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622516/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Stamp Duty Land Tax: Affordable Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of stamp duty reform on the availability of affordable accommodation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","50856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622517","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Chancellor has not met with representatives of Wells Fargo bank.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-03T15:33:05.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622517/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622517/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Wells Fargo","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has met representatives of Wells Fargo bank to discuss the selling of financial products by that bank.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","50870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622518","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-03","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet regularly with the Financial Conduct Authority to discuss relevant regulatory issues.</p><p> </p><p>As was the case with previous Administrations, it is not the Treasury's practice to provide details of all such discussions.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-03T15:30:08.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622518/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622518/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Lloyds Banking Group: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Financial Conduct Authority on the reported £16 billion set aside by Lloyds Banking Group for the mis-selling of payment protection insurance.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","50871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622519","Church Commissioners","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Church Commissioners are currently preparing a planning application for an urban extension at Norwood, Peterborough. We are in regular communication with Peterborough City Council and statutory consultees on key technical inputs to support the submission. The application will be made in outline and will be accompanied by an Environmental Statement, which will assess all relevant environmental matters. We anticipate that the planning application will be submitted in the new year.</p>","Meriden","Dame Caroline Spelman",,"2016-11-01T09:10:25.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622519/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622519/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-10-27","Church of England: Peterborough","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, what progress has been made on disposing of land at the urban extension at Norwood Peterborough with a view to submitting an outline planning application for residential development to Peterborough City Council; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","50857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622520","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-08","<p>The information is not centrally held in the form requested. Over the last year Government has acted to level the playing field for UK steel producers in light of the complex global challenges faced by the UK steel sector. Last December Government issued guidance to central government departments on how to ensure that they take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers when conducting their procurement activities. This guidance is also being extended to the wider public sector.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-11-08T12:29:15.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622520/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622520/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-27","Department for Communities and Local Government: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent estimate he has made of the level of procurement of British steel by his Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622521","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-04","<p>We have no made assessment of the economic impact of speedway, but recognise it as an important part of the domestic motorsports sector, which not only contributes economically, but entertains spectators, and is enjoyed by over 20000 participants a week.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-04T13:17:41.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622521/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622521/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Motor Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the economic contribution of speedway to the economy.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","50686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622522","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Prime Minister’s Tourism Action Plan reaffirms this Government's commitment to growing the industry right across the UK. Progress is already being made, with the South East, South West, West Midlands and North East seeing international visits and spend grow at a faster rate than London</p><p>​</p><p>However, there is more to be done in order to ensure that the benefits of tourism are shared across all cities, regions and nations up and down the UK and we will be working hard to make this happen.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-01T17:51:35.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622522/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622522/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Government's five point plan for tourism in achieving its aims.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","50675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622523","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-04","<p>One of the primary objectives of the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) is to support the growth of the UK’s Digital Economy and encourage the development and adoption of new technologies across all sectors. Officials in many teams in the Department work on policies and interventions to create the right environment for this growth, whether it is improving digital infrastructure and digital skills or supporting digital enterprise and the creative industries.</p><p> </p><p>The Government gives direct support to the development of new technologies through organisations such as InnovateUK and the Digital Catapult.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-04T10:48:57.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622523/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622523/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many officials of her Department are employed to work specifically on developing new technologies.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","50676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622524","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-04","<p>Ministers and officials regularly meet with Visit England, as well as Visit Britain to actively discuss a range of issues affecting the industry. Through the £40m Discover England Fund, which aims to encourage tourists to travel outside of London, we are developing world class itineraries and new tourist products.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-11-04T13:16:35.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622524/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622524/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with Visit England on increasing tourism outside London.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","50677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622525","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-04","<p>Following a consultation across the sector, new regulations were put in place on 1 April 2015. These regulations seek to balance necessary regulation of a varied sector and support for this important group. The Government will continue to monitor the regulation and effectiveness of charitable tax reliefs within the scheme and more widely.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-04T14:04:12.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622525/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622525/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-27","Sports: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to reduce the level of regulation on community and amateur sports clubs.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","50685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622526","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-07","<p>Social mix is at the core of National Citizen Service. DCMS and NCS Trust take great care to ensure that all young people, regardless of background, are able to take part in the programme. The cost of participation is up to £50. Partial and full bursaries are provided on a means-tested basis for young people whose families are unable to meet the cost.</p><p> </p><p>NCS Trust was established in 2013. Between 2013 and 2015, NCS Trust data shows that 136,514 participants received some financial assistance. The completion rate for this group was in line with the national average with over 90% completing the programme.</p><p> </p><p>Data is not available for 2011-2012 when the programme was run by Cabinet Office.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-07T09:47:48.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622526/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622526/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Voluntary Work: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) participants and (b) people who have completed the National Citizenship Service received financial assistance for the £50 application fee since that service was introduced.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","50746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622527","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-01","<p>The NCS Bill is focused on the transformation of the Trust into a Royal Charter body. Given that all costs association with this transition will be directly funded by government, an impact assessment will not be required.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-01T17:24:56.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622527/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622527/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","National Citizen Service Bill (HL): Impact Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when she plans to publish an impact assessment for the National Citizen Service Bill [HL].","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","50747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622528","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that the UK seizes the chance to be a world leader in the development of 5G, and the UK has actively participated in the global process for setting 5G standards.</p><p> </p><p>We have asked the Future Communications Challenge Group (FCCG) of senior academics, industry experts and funders to consider how to drive forward the Government's commitment in this area. In parallel the National Infrastructure Commission (NIC) is conducting a study, launched at Budget 2016, into how the UK can achieve early deployment of 5G networks. These reports will feed into a comprehensive 5G strategy for the UK, to be published in 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-04T14:32:24.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622528/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622528/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","5G","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress her Department has made on developing capacity to implement the policy of making the UK a world leader in the development of 5G technologies.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","50674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622529","Home Office","false","2016-11-11","<p>There will be no immediate changes to our relationship with the EU. This means that EEA, Swiss and UK nationals continue to have the same rights and status that they had before the referendum.</p><p>The government will provide strong and proven leadership as Britain begins its negotiations to leave the European Union and forge a new role for ourselves in the world. We will work hard to get the right deal: one that is unique to Britain and not an ‘off the shelf’ solution. This must mean controls on the numbers of people who come to Britain from Europe - but also a positive outcome for those who wish to trade in goods and services.</p><p>We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out further positions in advance. We are also not going to provide a running commentary on every twist and turn of these negotiations. At every step of these negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","50736","2016-11-11T16:53:41.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622529/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622529/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Tourism: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on the tourism industry of the introduction of visa charges on travel to and from the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","50735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622530","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Government is dedicated to ensuring that arts and cultural experiences like museums and galleries benefit everyone and not just the privileged few. That is why we are committed to retaining free access to the permanent national collections. Since the introduction of free access in 2001, visits to DCMS-sponsored museums and galleries have increased by over 150%.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-04T14:31:09.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622530/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622530/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Museums and Galleries: Low Incomes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will take steps to ensure that low income families have free access to museums and galleries.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","50673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622531","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-01","<p>Ofcom consulted on mobile switching and mobile contracts notice periods earlier this year and is currently considering responses to those consultations, with an expectation to make a statement on mobile switching in spring 2017. The Government would like to see consumers starting to benefit from these switching process measures as soon as possible. The Digital Economy Bill will make it easier for consumers to switch by requiring communications providers to follow any new procedures set by Ofcom when customers wish to change provider.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-01T11:33:04.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622531/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622531/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Mobile Phones: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the effect on consumers of the time taken to implement switching in the mobile market to a gaining provider-led system.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","50703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622532","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-01","<p>Ofcom consulted on mobile switching and mobile contracts notice periods earlier this year. Ofcom is now considering responses to those consultations and expects to make a statement on mobile switching in spring 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-01T11:34:20.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622532/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622532/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Mobile Phones: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what information she holds of when Ofcom plans to bring forward its proposals to reform switching in the mobile market.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","50704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622533","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is committed to making switching communications provider easier for all consumers, including for vulnerable people. The Digital Economy Bill will make it easier for consumers to switch by requiring communications providers to follow any new procedures set by Ofcom when customers wish to change provider.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom consulted on mobile switching and mobile contracts notice periods earlier this year. Ofcom is now considering responses to those consultations and expects to make a statement on mobile switching in spring 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-01T11:35:05.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622533/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622533/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Mobile Phones: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the effect on vulnerable consumers of the current switching regime in the mobile market.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","50705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622534","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-14","<p>The journals and periodicals the Department currently subscribes to include:</p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>Wired</li><li>The Spectator</li><li>The New Statesman</li><li>The Week</li><li>Private Eye</li><li>Enders</li><li>Broadcast</li><li>EU Media Observatory</li><li>IBIS World</li></ul><p> </p><p>DCMS also has an account with EBSCOhost, which provides access to many varied academic journals.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-14T16:55:33.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622534/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622534/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Press","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, to which journals and periodicals her Department currently subscribes.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","50671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622535","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-01","<p>For the 2016 summer programme, 4% of participants reported that they attend independent schools (2,550 young people). NCS Trust does not currently hold school data for all participants, so this figure represents the proportion of those who provided their school details.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-01T17:23:15.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622535/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622535/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Voluntary Work: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of National Citizen Service participants are from independent schools.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","50706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622536","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-01","<p>Consecutive, independent evaluations have demonstrated that National Citizen Service (NCS) delivers social and economic benefits. The most recently published evaluation shows that 90% of participants said that NCS helped them to develop key skills for the future. Annual evaluation reports on NCS are available on the NCS website (<a href="http://www.ncsyes.co.uk/our-impact" target="_blank">www.ncsyes.co.uk/our-impact</a>).</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-11-01T17:24:05.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622536/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622536/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Voluntary Work: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the social and economic benefits of the National Citizen Service; and when she plans to publish an evaluation report on that service.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","50707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622537","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that arts and cultural experiences like museums and galleries benefit everyone and not just the privileged few.</p><p> </p><p>Our Culture White Paper set out Government’s expectation that all cultural organisations in receipt of public money should reach out to everyone regardless of background, education or geography. Earlier this month Arts Council England announced the ambition to achieve a 4% uplift in the proportion of the budget spent outside London in their 2018-22 investment.</p><p> </p><p>Already this year National Museums Liverpool has seen an 7% increase in the number of visits compared to this time last year. In the coming months DCMS aims to pilot different schemes to increase visitors to museums outside London and expand the ones that work, such as the Cultural Citizens pilot with Kids in Museums in Birmingham. The Museums Review will look at evidence and make further recommendations on widening participation.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-01T11:36:16.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622537/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622537/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Museums and Galleries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will take steps to increase the numbers of visits to museums and galleries outside London.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","50672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622538","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-04","<p>In light of the Government’s manifesto commitment to achieve three million new apprenticeship starts in England by the end of the Parliament, the Cabinet Office will be centrally collecting data on apprenticeships to allow the Civil Service to report on its contribution towards the national target.</p><p> </p><p>DCMS employed four apprenticeships in the 2014 calendar year, five in 2015 and three in 2016 to date. All of these apprentices were recruited on permanent Civil Service contracts. Data on apprentices was separately recorded from 2014.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-11-04T10:53:27.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622538/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622538/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-27","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many apprenticeships have been created in her Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622539","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-11-04","<p>This information is not held in the format requested. The Cabinet Office is currently coordinating a detailed data collection from across Government including the apprenticeship type, region of work, as well as demographic data and socio-economic background. This will allow the Civil Service to report on its contribution towards the national target. Information on the number of apprenticeships created in the Ministry of Defence in each of the last five years is shown below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of Apprenticeships</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>68</p></td><td><p>121</p></td><td><p>181</p></td><td><p>346</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Armed Forces are the biggest provider of apprenticeships within the UK. Completion rates for Level 2 and Level 3 apprenticeships in the Armed Forces by Academic Year for 2011-12 and 2012-13 are shown below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Level 2 Apprenticeships - 1 August 2011- 31 July 2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Level 2 Apprenticeships - 1 August 2012- 31 July 2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Level 3 Apprenticeships - 1 August 2011- 31 July 2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Level 3 Apprenticeships - 1 August 2012- 31 July 2013</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Army</strong></p></td><td><p>4,507</p></td><td><p>3,116</p></td><td><p>1,682</p></td><td><p>1,763</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Royal Navy</strong></p></td><td><p>2,182</p></td><td><p>2,006</p></td><td><p>339</p></td><td><p>334</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Royal Air Force</strong></p></td><td><p>764</p></td><td><p>693</p></td><td><p>665</p></td><td><p>618</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>7,864*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>5,891*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,134*</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,893*</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*total numbers include apprenticeships completed by Service personnel.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-11-04T13:52:29.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622539/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622539/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-27","Ministry of Defence: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many apprenticeships have been created in his Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50804"
