"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622625","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Clinical Priorities Advisory Group has not considered Afinator for the treatment of breast cancer.</p><p> </p><p>Afinitor is one of four breast cancer treatments currently available through the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF), where certain criteria apply. Afinitor will remain available through the CDF while it is being reappraised by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence as part of the transition to the new CDF model.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-03T12:04:23.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622625/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622625/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Breast Cancer: Everolimus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on what evidence the Clinical Priorities Advisory Board based its decision to not fund the use of Afinitor for the treatment of breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","50731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622626","Department of Health","false","2016-11-02","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health has held no discussions with the Secretary of State for Defence on provision for a families and civilian general practice surgery outside the wire at MOD Lyneham.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-02T13:59:07.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622626/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622626/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","General Practitioners: MOD Lyneham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has had discussions with the Secretary of State for Defence on provision for a families and civilian GP surgery outside the wire at MOD Lyneham.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","50712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622627","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>Decisions about local health services are for local determination. My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health has had no recent discussions on the provision of general practitioner surgeries in Wiltshire and has no current plans to visit Wiltshire.</p><p> </p><p>We are advised by NHS England that the plans for a branch surgery in Lyneham were declined by the Primary Care Joint Commissioning Committee for Wiltshire, because a Local Authority Needs Assessment decided that there was no unmet health need in Lyneham. However, the Committee has identified a number of areas for improved service delivery and NHS England is working with local providers to address this.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","50726","2016-11-03T12:02:55.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622627/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622627/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","General Practitioners: Wiltshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent discussions he has had on the provision of GP surgeries in Wiltshire.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","50725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622628","Department of Health","false","2016-11-03","<p>Decisions about local health services are for local determination. My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health has had no recent discussions on the provision of general practitioner surgeries in Wiltshire and has no current plans to visit Wiltshire.</p><p> </p><p>We are advised by NHS England that the plans for a branch surgery in Lyneham were declined by the Primary Care Joint Commissioning Committee for Wiltshire, because a Local Authority Needs Assessment decided that there was no unmet health need in Lyneham. However, the Committee has identified a number of areas for improved service delivery and NHS England is working with local providers to address this.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","50725","2016-11-03T12:02:55.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622628/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622628/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","General Practitioners: Lyneham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will visit Wiltshire to assess the need for a GP surgery in Lyneham.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","50726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622629","Department of Health","false","2016-11-01","<p>Young women have emerged as a high risk group in the Adult Psychiatric Morbidity Survey, including positive screens for posttraumatic stress disorder. The Adult Psychiatric Morbidity Survey and the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health report have highlighted issues of mental health inequalities; both in relation to risk of developing mental health problems, and in accessing services when mental health problems develop. In response to recommendations made by the Task Force, the Department is in the process of developing a mental health equalities work programme for the next five years. The development which will be informed by a roundtable this autumn formed of expert stakeholders and service users and carers. The data produced by the Adult Psychiatric Morbidity Survey, and the equalities issues it raises, will directly inform the roundtable discussion and the subsequent content and focus of the work programme.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-01T16:52:59.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622629/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622629/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Post-traumatic Stress Disorder: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Adult Psychiatric Morbidity Survey: Survey of Mental Health and Wellbeing, England, 2014, published on 29 September 2016, what plans he has to address the increase in the incidence of post-traumatic stress disorder in young women; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","50751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622630","Department of Health","false","2016-11-01","<p>Information is not held centrally in the format requested.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-01T17:35:13.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622630/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622630/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Family Nurse Partnership Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many families have been assisted by the Family Nurse Partnership in (a) Liverpool, Wavertree constituency, (b) Liverpool, (c) the Liverpool City Region and (d) each region in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","50750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622631","Department of Health","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Department has procured no steel directly in the last 12 months. Where required, the majority of steel is purchased by the National Health Service and this is a local decision with no data collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The contractors on the Department’s Procure21+ framework have confirmed that approximately 3,000 tonnes of British steel was procured by them for projects delivered for and by the NHS in the last 12 months. We are unable to provide estimates for projects delivered outside the P21+ framework as this would require writing to each NHS organisation and would incur a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The Department promulgates all central guidance on the procurement of steel to the NHS, including the Cabinet Office Guidance ‘Procurement Practise Note 16/15 - procuring steel in major projects’ and has included this as a contractual requirement in the new Procure22 design and construction framework.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-04T14:30:41.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622631/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622631/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Department of Health: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent estimate he has made of the level of procurement of British steel by his Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622632","Department of Health","false","2016-11-01","<p>The redesign and delivery of front-line health services is a matter for the local National Health Service – clinically led by front line NHS organisations and clinicians who are closest to the needs of communities and therefore best-placed to make decisions in the interests of their patients.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England leads on reconfiguration policy. There has been no formal assessment of accident and emergency departments that will see a reduction in their opening hours by 2020.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-01T16:50:55.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622632/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622632/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Accident and Emergency Departments: Opening Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the number of accident and emergency departments that will reduce their opening hours by 2020; and which accident and emergency departments a decision has been reached on reducing open hours.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","50656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622633","Department of Health","false","2016-11-04","<p>The information needed to make such an estimate is not collected centrally. Employers are responsible for managing sickness absence of their staff and taking action to support their health and wellbeing so they can stay at work and many already provide access to physiotherapy for musculoskeletal problems as well as counselling for mental health and stress.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is leading a £5 million campaign to improve the physical and mental health and wellbeing of National Health Service staff working with Public Health England, NHS Employers and trusts across the NHS. They are creating capacity to improve help for staff on the major causes of ill health including access to physiotherapy and mental health talking therapies, as well as smoking cessation and weight management services. Subject to evaluation at 10 trusts, these services will be rolled out more widely in due course.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-04T09:34:05.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622633/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622633/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","NHS: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the cost to the NHS of its staff being unable to work because of lack of availability of medical treatment funded by clinical commissioning groups.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","50657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622634","Department of Health","false","2016-11-02","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has appraised the PCSK9 inhibitors alirocumab (Praluent) and evolocumab (Repatha) for treating primary hypercholesterolaemia and mixed dyslipidaemia. In June 2016, NICE issued final technology appraisal guidance recommending both treatments, subject to certain criteria. Further information is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/conditions-and-diseases/diabetes-and-other-endocrinal--nutritional-and-metabolic-conditions/lipid-disorders" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/conditions-and-diseases/diabetes-and-other-endocrinal--nutritional-and-metabolic-conditions/lipid-disorders</a></p><p> </p><p>NHS Commissioners are legally required to fund drugs and treatments recommended in NICE technology appraisal guidance within three months of its final guidance being issued.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","50562","2016-11-02T14:10:41.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622634/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622634/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Cholesterol: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of funding for people with high cholesterol to access PCSK9 inhibitors for the treatment of that condition.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","50629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622635","Department of Health","false","2016-11-01","<p>The information requested is in the attached document.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-01T14:15:04.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622635/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622635/answer","PQ50693 GP list sizes Wiltshire 31st Oct.xlsx","PQ50693 GP list sizes Wiltshire 31st Oct","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622635/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Doctors' List of Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average number of patients per GP surgery is in (a) England, (b) Wiltshire, (c) Royal Wootton Bassett and (d) Calne.","false","Biography information for James Gray","North Wiltshire","James Gray","50693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622636","Department of Health","false","2016-11-01","<p>The procurement of local health services by means of competitive tendering is a matter for the local National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is accountable for ensuring that the health services which both it and clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) commission are of high quality and deliver value for money. The CCG Improvement and Assessment Framework has been designed to provide confidence to internal and external stakeholders and the wider public that CCGs are operating effectively to commission safe, high-quality and sustainable services within their resources.</p><p> </p><p>We are informed by NHS England that Greenwich CCG follows standard NHS procurement procedures and that these procedures were followed for this procurement. We understand that the detailed clinical service specification will be used to hold the provider to account within the format of the NHS national standard contract.</p><p> </p><p>We are further advised that this procurement has been subject to NHS England’s assurance process for this type of contract.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-01T17:44:23.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622636/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622636/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Circle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether a formal assessment of the effect of awarding the contract for provision of muscular skeletal services to Circle Health at Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trusts was carried out by (a) Greenwich Clinical Commissioning Group and (b) NHS England.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","50660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622637","Department of Health","false","2016-11-02","<p>Decisions about the commissioning and decommissioning of local National Health Service services are a matter for clinical commissioning groups (CCGs). We would expect CCGs to make all decisions regarding the commissioning and commissioning of services based on the needs of their local communities. We would also expect CCGs to carefully consider all factors relating to the delivery of high quality and efficient health services that meet quality standards and achieve the best outcomes for the communities. Local commissioning decisions should be supported, where appropriate, by robust consultation with the local community.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-02T14:12:27.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622637/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622637/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to increase the use of clinical answering services for commissioning and decommissioning of treatment and support relating to mental health.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","50680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622638","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>DNA testing is not carried out or required for immigration applications. Information regarding DNA tests submitted by applicants is not aggregated in national reporting systems. This information could only be obtained by a manual case by case review to collate the data, which would be disproportionately expensive.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T14:15:23.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622638/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622638/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many times DNA testing has been used in immigration cases in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","50678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622639","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Home Office publishes the number of age disputes raised in each quarter in table as_10_q, in volume 3 of the asylum data tables: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546760/asylum3-q2-2016-tabs.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546760/asylum3-q2-2016-tabs.ods</a></p><p>The numbers of disputed cases are reported in section 13 ‘Age Disputes’ of the Asylum chapter, in the Immigration Statistics release: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2016/asylum" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2016/asylum</a></p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T14:13:35.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622639/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622639/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many times her Department has disputed the age of someone claiming to be a child when making an asylum application in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622640","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The minimum income threshold of £18,600 for sponsoring a non-EEA partner to come to the UK prevents burdens on the taxpayer and promotes integration. It was set following advice from the independent Migration Advisory Committee and reflects the income at which a family settled in the UK generally ceases to be able to access income-related benefits. The policy has been approved by Parliament and upheld as lawful by the courts.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T14:08:40.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622640/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622640/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Entry Clearances: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department plans to change the £18,600 income threshold for immigration of non-EEA partners of British citizens.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","50651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622641","Department of Health","false","2016-11-01","<p>Yes, ethnicity and physical restraint are required elements of the Mental Health Services Data Set.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-01T16:56:48.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622641/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622641/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Restraint Techniques: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether mental health providers are required in recording data on the use of physical restraint to record the ethnicity of the person against whom such restraint is used.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","50661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622642","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Home Office does not hold information on the number of times that any police officers or other police staff have been deployed to a mental health unit or deployed to recall a person on a mental health treatment order in the community to return them to hospital.</p><p>Police deployments are an operational matter for the relevant police force.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","50663","2016-11-07T13:47:12.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622642/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622642/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Police: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department holds information on the number of times (a) territorial support groups and (b) other police officers have been deployed to a mental health unit in response to a request from a provider in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","50662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622643","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Home Office does not hold information on the number of times that any police officers or other police staff have been deployed to a mental health unit or deployed to recall a person on a mental health treatment order in the community to return them to hospital.</p><p>Police deployments are an operational matter for the relevant police force.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","50662","2016-11-07T13:47:12.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622643/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622643/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Police: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department holds information on the number of times (a) territorial support groups and (b) other police officers have been deployed to recall a person on a mental heath treatment order in the community and to return them to hospital in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","50663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622644","Home Office","false","2016-12-09","<p>The decision to procure and deploy body worn video (BWV) cameras is an operational one for chief officers. The Home Office is aware that most forces in England and Wales use BWV to some extent. Each force will have its own implementation plan and schedule for the rollout of cameras. This information is not held centrally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-12-09T16:17:35.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622644/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622644/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress has been made on the rollout of body-worn cameras to police officers for the collection of evidence.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","50684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622645","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Home Office does not publish this data by calendar year. The Home Office compiles its Annual Report and Accounts by financial year. The Annual Report and Accounts 2015-16 can be found on the .gov.uk website</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T13:52:25.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622645/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622645/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","UK Visas and Immigration: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was spent on (a) food, (b) drinks, (c) rail fares, (d) air fares, (e) mileage allowances, (f) taxis, (g) other travel costs, (h) room hire and (i) accommodation for staff by UK Visas and Immigration in the first nine months of 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","50714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622646","Home Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>I refer the honourable gentleman to the answer that was given to question 49304 on 2 November 2016.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-02T16:18:48.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622646/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622646/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 21 October 2016 to Question 49304, on correspondence with Judge Goddard, when she plans to provide a substantive reply to that Question.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","50694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622647","Home Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>All members of staff who make decisions in asylum receive the same level of training. This includes a dedicated five-week foundation training programme that includes training on international and domestic law and safeguarding issues supplemented by a mentoring programme with an experienced caseworker that can last up to 6 months. Within this course there are specific sections that detail torture and Medico Legal Reports and how they should be used and analysed in asylum claims.</p><p>Asylum Operations recently received funding from the Asylum Migration and Integration Fund to review and redevelop its training prospectus. As part of that work, Asylum Operations is liaising with a range of external stakeholders -including migrant charities and non-governmental organisations - to ensure a robust and effectivesafeguarding training product.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-02T09:58:14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622647/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622647/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what training asylum caseworkers receive on processing and considering asylum claims involving allegations of torture or serious harm where a Medico-Legal report from the Medical Foundation Medico-Legal Report Service at Freedom from Torture or the Helen Bamber Foundation forms part of the evidence.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","50648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622648","Home Office","false","2016-11-17","<p>The information is not centrally held in the form requested. Over the last year Government has acted to level the playing field for UK steel producers in light of the complex global challenges faced by the UK steel sector. Last December Government issued guidance to central government departments on how to ensure that they take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers when conducting their procurement activities. This guidance is also being extended to the wider public sector.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-17T17:06:05.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622648/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622648/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Home Office: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent estimate she has made of the level of procurement of British steel by her Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622649","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government receives a large number of reports from a range of organisations (including Detention Action) and takes them into account, as appropriate, in developing its policies and strategies.</p><p>Our published policy is clear that alternatives to detention should be used wherever possible, and we will continue to use detention to tackle immigration abuse by enforcing removal when necessary. Depriving someone of their liberty will always be subject to careful consideration and scrutiny, and will take account of individual circumstances.</p><p>The Government commissioned an independent review of the welfare of vulnerable individuals in detention by Stephen Shaw. We accepted the broad thrust of Mr Shaw’s recommendations, including the adoption of a wider definition of those at risk, and we have strengthened our policies and processes for dealing with the detention of persons who may be vulnerable.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T13:58:37.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622649/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622649/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Immigration: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policy on migrant detention of the report published by Detention Action entitled, Without detention, on 26 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","50733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622650","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>The information requested is not centrally held by the Home Office.</p><p>The Office for National Statistics publish data collected by the Home Office on the number of recorded crimes of ‘possession of article with blade or point’ but this is not broken down by age. Additionally, the Home Office publishes data at the police force and Community Safety Partnership area in Open Data Tables, which can be found here: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</p><p>The Home Office publishes arrests by each police force in England and Wales at offence group level only. It is not possible to tell from these data how many arrests related to knife crimes.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","50785","2016-11-14T17:26:02.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622650/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622650/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Knives: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people under the age of 18 have been found in possession of a knife in (a) London and (b) Bethnal Green and Bow constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","50727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622651","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>We plan to consult local government, non-governmental organisations and other partners on the regulations to be made under section 95A, concerning support for failed asylum seekers who face a genuine obstacle to their departure from the UK at the point their appeal rights are exhausted.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-08T17:13:51.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622651/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622651/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to consult on regulations to be made under section 95A of the Immigration and Asylum Act 1999 as inserted by Schedule 11 of the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","50722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622652","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Immigration Enforcement Business Plan for 2016 -17 will be published in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T13:54:01.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622652/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622652/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Immigration Enforcement Directorate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to publish her Department's Immigration Enforcement Business Plan for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","50732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622653","Home Office","false","2016-11-09","<p>The Home Office has raised the process of second post mortem authorisation with the Chief Coroner who has produced proposed changes in line with Hutton recommendation that are currently out for consultation with key stakeholders.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-09T16:07:23.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622653/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622653/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Post-mortems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendation made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that second post-mortems are only authorised following a formal application to a coroner or judge and become a desktop review of the first report.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622654","Home Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>This recommendation is part of potential wider structural change that forms part of advice on options, currently being considered by Home Office Ministers, for taking forward the recommendations in the Hutton Review of forensic pathology in England and Wales.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","50737 ; 50865","2016-11-04T18:10:39.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622654/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622654/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Forensic Pathology in England and Wales Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendation made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that regional centres should be established.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622655","Home Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>This recommendation is part of potential wider structural change that forms part of advice on options, currently being considered by Home Office Ministers, for taking forward the recommendations in the Hutton Review of forensic pathology in England and Wales.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","50717 ; 50865","2016-11-04T18:10:39.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622655/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622655/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Pathology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken in response to the recommendation in paragraph 4.1.4 of the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales on (a) introducing a publicly-funded salaried service for forensic pathologists and (b) job planning coronial autopsy sessions within NHS contracts.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622656","Home Office","false","2016-11-11","<p>There will be no immediate changes to our relationship with the EU. This means that EEA, Swiss and UK nationals continue to have the same rights and status that they had before the referendum.</p><p>The government will provide strong and proven leadership as Britain begins its negotiations to leave the European Union and forge a new role for ourselves in the world. We will work hard to get the right deal: one that is unique to Britain and not an ‘off the shelf’ solution. This must mean controls on the numbers of people who come to Britain from Europe - but also a positive outcome for those who wish to trade in goods and services.</p><p>We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out further positions in advance. We are also not going to provide a running commentary on every twist and turn of these negotiations. At every step of these negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","50735","2016-11-11T16:53:41.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622656/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622656/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Visas: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on (a) families and (b) businesses of the introduction of visa charges on travel to and from the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","50736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622657","Home Office","false","2016-11-16","<p>The Home Office has consulted with the National Police Chiefs’ Council’s UK Disaster Victim Identification Unit who have stated that their systems for mass fatality incidents are in line with the recommendation in the Hutton review.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-16T17:31:50.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622657/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622657/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Pathology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendation made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that non-forensic pathologists engaged in mass fatality incidents should work under the supervision of a Home Office Registered Forensic Pathologist.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622658","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>There was no charge for the venue and no cost to the public purse for refreshments.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T13:49:52.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622658/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622658/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","UK Visas and Immigration: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost was to the public purse of (a) room hire, (b) food and (c) hot and cold drinks for the UK Visas and Immigration North West MP Account Manager Team Regional Event held at Manchester Civil Justice Centre on 16 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","50713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622659","Home Office","false","2016-11-16","<p>The Home Office has consulted with both the police (through the National Police Chiefs’ Council’s Homicide Working Group) and all six forensic pathology group practices over this recommendation. Following a review of current arrangements it was agreed not to implement this recommendation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-16T17:31:35.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622659/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622659/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Pathology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendation made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that the User Requirements for Forensic Pathology form the basis for more formal contractual arrangements with the police.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622660","Home Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>This recommendation is part of potential wider structural change that forms part of advice on options, currently being considered by Home Office Ministers, for taking forward the recommendations in the Hutton Review of forensic pathology in England and Wales.</p><p>The Home Office is not responsible for police procedures but has worked with the National Police Chiefs’ Council and the College of Policing in revising national policy for first officers attending in line with the Hutton recommendation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-04T18:10:56.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622660/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622660/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Pathology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendations made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that (a) there needs to be greater interchange between forensic and general pathology training systems and (b) the threshold for referring such cases up the supervisory ladder should be low.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622661","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Home Office does not have legal authority in Turkey to confiscate foreign passports which have been reported as lost or stolen or identified as forged.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T14:22:53.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622661/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622661/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Passports: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passports have been confiscated from Syrian citizens by UK officials in Turkey in 2016 on the basis of those passports having been stolen.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","50784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622662","Home Office","false","2016-11-14","<p>The information requested is not centrally held by the Home Office.</p><p>The Office for National Statistics publish data collected by the Home Office on the number of recorded crimes of ‘possession of article with blade or point’ but this is not broken down by age. Additionally, the Home Office publishes data at the police force and Community Safety Partnership area in Open Data Tables, which can be found here: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</p><p>The Home Office publishes arrests by each police force in England and Wales at offence group level only. It is not possible to tell from these data how many arrests related to knife crimes.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","50727","2016-11-14T17:26:02.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622662/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622662/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Knives: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many arrests for knife crimes have taken place in (a) London and (b) Bethnal Green and Bow in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","50785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622663","Home Office","false","2016-11-09","<p>The Home Office Homicide Index contains information on homicides recorded by the police at the police force area level. Data on the number of homicides recorded by the police in London where the method of killing was by shooting are given in the Table.</p><p>The data refer to the position as at 13 November 2015, when the Homicide Index was frozen for the purpose of analysis.</p><p>Information on homicides recorded in 2015/16 will be published by the Office for National Statistics in February 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Table: Homicide offences<sup>1</sup> recorded by the police in London<sup>2</sup> where the method of killing was by shooting</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of offences</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1. Source: Homicide Index, Home Office</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>2. London includes City of London and Metropolitan Police</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-09T16:29:42.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622663/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622663/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Firearms: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many gun-related homicides have taken place in (a) London and (b) Bethnal Green and Bow in each year since 2005.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","50786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622664","Home Office","false","2016-11-08","<p>We expect social media companies, and internet platforms, to have robust processes in place and to act promptly when abuse, including threats of rape and sexual violence, is reported. The Government continues to work closely with social media companies and other relevant actors and experts to make sure they are committed to protecting those who use their platforms.</p><p>The Criminal Justice Act 2015 strengthened two existing communications offences: section 1 of the Malicious Communications Act 1988, and section 127 of the Communications Act 2003 which can now be used to prosecute misuse of social media. The police now have longer to investigate either offence, and the maximum penalty for the former has been increased to two years imprisonment.</p><p>The Crown Prosecution Service has published guidance to prosecutors this month on crimes involving social media, with a specific focus on Violence Against Women and Girls (VAWG) offences. This includes guidance that communications that contain images or videos of women with very serious injuries, or of women being raped, or of women being subjected to sadistic acts of violence, accompanied by text that suggests that such assaults / rape / acts are acceptable or desirable may well be considered grossly offensive and prosecuted either under section 1 of the Malicious Communications Act 1988 or under section 127 of the Communications Act 2003.</p><p>The Home Office has allocated £4.6m of the Police Transformation Fund specifically to begin the critical work of setting up a comprehensive and joined up programme of digital transformation across policing. This money will help provide a step-change in digital capability, including a Digital Investigation and Intelligence (DII) programme, which will build police capability in relation to the skills and technology required to respond to the full range of digital crime types.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-08T16:12:41.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622664/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622664/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Sexual Offences: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to counter threats of rape and sexual violence made through (a) social media networks, (b) Whatsapp and (c) Twitter.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","50787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622665","Home Office","false","2016-11-16","<p>This recommendation was initially considered as part of the review of the Forensic Archive Ltd. This review has now been published and recommended not to provide a central secure store for forensic pathology case material. The Home Office has taken steps to include changes into the next revision of the Forensic Science Regulator’s Codes of Practice and Performance Standards publication in line with the Hutton recommendation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-16T17:31:22.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622665/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622665/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Post-mortems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendation made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that as a temporary measure to ensure that sensitive material (such as notes, photographs and copy statements) from forensic autopsies are kept in secure locations, and all unused material should be stored with the police file as is normally the case with all other unused material.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622666","Home Office","false","2016-11-11","<p>A planned trial of the use of voluntary dental x-rays in the age assessment process did not go ahead in 2012.</p><p>The Home Secretary's oral statement on Calais on 24 October (Column 55) referred to the proper safeguarding, age assessment and security checks we carry out, working closely with local authorities and social workers in the UK, to ensure that the children transferred here are eligible to come and it is in their best interests to do so.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-11T15:47:53.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622666/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622666/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Asylum: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 23 May 2012 to Question 106405 on asylum: young people, what the results of the dental x-ray pilot were.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","50781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622667","Home Office","false","2016-11-15","<p>In light of the Government’s manifesto commitment to achieve three million new appren-ticeship starts in England by the end of the Parliament, the Cabinet Office will be centrally collecting data on apprenticeships to allow the Civil Service to report on its contribution towards the national target.</p><p>Prior to 1st April 2015 the Home Department did not centrally record apprenticeships.</p><p>From 1st April 2015 to 31st March 2016 there were 30 apprentices who started in the Home Department. From 1st April 2016 to date (as of 28/10/16) 45 apprentices started in the Home Department.</p><p>All of apprentices that started post 1st April 2015 are only part way through their assignments and therefore have not secured permanent positions within the civil service.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-15T16:57:32.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622667/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622667/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Home Office: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many apprenticeships have been created in her Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622668","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>I refer the Hon member to my answer to PQ 48562.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-03T16:21:47.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622668/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622668/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2016 to Question 48562, how many of the families of the victims of the 61 prisoners (a) were offered the chance to receive information about key developments in the relevant prisoner's sentence and (b) took up the offer to receive such information.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","50863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622669","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>I refer to my previous answer given on 12 October.</p><p> </p><p>The family of the victims in these cases have the statutory right to request conditions – such as an exclusion zone – for inclusion in an offender’s licence. Families of victims are asked for this information when release on temporary licence (ROTL) is being considered in the first instance. They are subsequently informed if a series of ROTLs begins, but are not normally told before each individual ROTL takes place.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-09T12:24:59.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622669/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622669/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2016 to Question 48562, how much notice was given to the family of each victim of the release on temporary licence of the offender.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","50864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622670","Home Office","false","2016-11-10","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) and the Courts are responsible for adhering to the Criminal Procedure Rules and the Home Office has made them aware of this recommendation in the Hutton Review. All Home Office pathologists are trained and aware of their obligations in this regard.</p><p>The decision to allow video links in court is for the Judge on application from the CPS on a case-by-case basis. The Home Office has made both the police service and the CPS aware of this recommendation in the Hutton Report and ensured that the use of such technology is discussed as part of Senior Investigation Officer training.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-10T16:47:02.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622670/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622670/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Pathology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendation made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that (a) the Criminal Procedure Rules should be vigorously enforced in order to avoid costly and unnecessary challenges by experts for the prosecution and the defence in court and (b) the provision for a judge to allow experts to give evidence via video link could be utilised in order to encourage more-sub-speciality medical experts to engage in the criminal justice process.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622671","Home Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Home Office has raised this recommendation with the police, Ministry of Justice and the Chief Coroner’s Office. In respect of Home Office forensic pathologists such issues are addressed in their two week Criminal Justice Course they attend prior to acceptance on the Home Office Register.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-04T18:11:09.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622671/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622671/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendation made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that pathologists and other clinicians, police and coroners and their officers all need to be sensitive to the difficulties surrounding communication and understanding that arise in a multi-cultural society when death occurs in order to do what is possible to manage the situation.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622672","Home Office","false","2016-11-04","<p>This recommendation is part of potential wider structural change that forms part of advice on options, currently being considered by Home Office Ministers, for taking forward the recommendations in the Hutton Review of forensic pathology in England and Wales.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","50717 ; 50737","2016-11-04T18:10:38.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622672/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622672/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Post-mortems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government has taken as a result of the recommendation made in the Hutton review of forensic pathology in England and Wales, submitted to the Minister of State for Crime and Prevention in March 2015, that consideration should be given to the current fee structure payable for autopsies and possibly revised on the basis that you get what you pay for.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","50865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622673","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-28","<p>Records going back to 2002 but excluding 2009 and 2010 show that, of the 61 prisoners referred to in the reply to Question 41032, this was the first release at Christmas in 40 cases, the second such release in 13 cases and the third such release in 8 cases. Data on releases during 2009 and 2010 are not available because of disruption in the supply of data due to the migration from one reporting system to another.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-28T16:45:07.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622673/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622673/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2016 to Question 41032, how many prisoners convicted of murder had previously been released on temporary licence over a Christmas period; and, in each such case, how many times each of those prisoners had previously been released at Christmas.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","50862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622674","Home Office","false","2016-11-07","<p>The clearance of the camp is a French-led operation, but we have been working very closely with the French authorities to ensure that it is delivered as safely as possible, and that children are properly protected. We are committed to ensuring that minors eligible to come to the UK under the Dublin Regulation or the wider criteria of the Dubs amendment continue to be transferred as quickly as possible.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-07T14:18:51.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622674/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622674/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the safety of unaccompanied refugee children who have not been placed in alternative accommodation or registered with the French authorities after the demolition of the camp in Calais; and what steps the Government is taking in conjunction with the French authorities to help ensure the safety of those children.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","50860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622675","Home Office","false","2016-11-18","<p>We do not hold information centrally on the number of illegal foreign registered vehicles seized and impounded in England. This is an operational matter for the police and other partner agencies.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-18T13:30:53.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622675/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622675/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-27","Motor Vehicles: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the article, DVLA works with the police and HM Revenue and Customs to crack down on illegal foreign registered vehicles, published on the GOV.UK website on 30 January 2015, how many foreign-registered cars were seized and impounded by each constabulary in England in each month between 1 January 2015 and 30 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","50859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622676","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-03","<p>In light of the Government’s manifesto commitment to achieve three million new apprenticeship starts in England by the end of the Parliament, the Cabinet Office will be centrally collecting data on apprenticeships to allow the Civil Service to report on its contribution towards the national target. In line with these commitments DFID’s targets are set as:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>2019/20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DFID’s target</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>With current in year planning DFID will exceed the target set for 2016/17.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Type of Apprenticeship/ Location</p></td><td><p>Fast Track</p></td><td><p>Operational Delivery</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Kilbride</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Totals</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>25</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>DFID’s commitment to central Government apprenticeships started during 2015/16, details as below. These apprenticeships will not finish until at least July 2017 and it is too early to know how many will secure a job within the Civil Service.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Type of Apprenticeship/ location</p></td><td><p>Fast Track</p></td><td><p>Operational Delivery</p></td><td><p>Totals</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Kilbride</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>DFID did sponsor two internal apprenticeships in 2012; both were successful in retaining employment with DFID.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-03T15:53:57.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622676/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622676/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-27","Department for International Development: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many apprenticeships have been created in her Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622677","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-03","<p>DFID does not procure steel.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-03T15:51:56.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622677/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622677/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-27","Department for International Development: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent estimate she has made of the level of procurement of British steel by her Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622678","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>The information is not centrally held in the form requested. Over the last year Government has acted to level the playing field for UK steel producers in light of the complex global challenges faced by the UK steel sector. Last December Government issued guidance to central government departments on how to ensure that they take full account of the value provided by UK steel producers when conducting their procurement activities. This guidance is also being extended to the wider public sector.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-03T17:47:47.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622678/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622678/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Ministry of Justice: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent estimate she has made of the level of procurement of British steel by her Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622679","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-07","<p>As the Justice Secretary has announced, we are investing over £100m in staffing, and will recruit an extra 2,500 prison officers to increase safety and support prisoners to reform.</p><p>We will apply for planning permission to redevelop the site of HMP &amp; YOI Glen Parva. If we successfully achieve planning permission at the site, HMP &amp; YOI Glen Parva would close and be replaced by a new, fit for purpose, facility.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-07T17:05:29.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622679/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622679/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Glen Parva Young Offender Institution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent assessment her Department has made of the adequacy of the ratio of staff to young people at HMP Glen Parva in 2016; and what the adequacy of such ratios is up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Alberto Costa","South Leicestershire","Alberto Costa","50652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622682","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>Information on the regional location of apprenticeships is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>In light of the Government’s manifesto commitment to achieve three million new apprenticeship starts in England by the end of the Parliament, the Cabinet Office will be centrally collecting data on apprenticeships to allow the Civil Service to report on its contribution towards the national target.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-03T17:28:16.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622682/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622682/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Ministry of Justice: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many apprenticeships have been created in her Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622683","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government’s Transforming Rehabilitation programme included the extension of licensed supervision to those receiving sentences of under 12 months. This was brought into effect by the Offender Rehabilitation Act 2014 in February 2015. Before that, the prison into which recalled offenders were received was not recorded centrally. The number of women received into each prison under licence recall for sentences of all lengths in the 12 months since February 2015 is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>Bronzefield 246</p><p>Eastwood Park 194</p><p>Foston Hall 120</p><p>Holloway 108</p><p>Low Newton 67</p><p>New Hall 159</p><p>Peterborough 159</p><p>Styal 211</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-07T14:47:37.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622683/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622683/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Prisoners' Release: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many women were received into each prison under licence recall in the 12 months (a) prior to and (b) following the introduction of Transforming Rehabilitation.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","50840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622684","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>The Offender Rehabilitation Act 2014, which introduced licence and post sentence supervision for those serving short custodial sentences, applies to offences committed on or after 1 February 2015. Final proven reoffending data for those serving sentences imposed after the changes to the supervision of short sentences is not yet available. As with all new legislation, the operation of recall is kept under review.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","50838","2016-11-09T12:18:16.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622684/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622684/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Prisoners' Release: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of 14-day recalls for women who breach their licence conditions in reducing future offending.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","50839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622685","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) provide rehabilitation and resettlement services to all offenders. We are committed to giving female offenders the help and support they need to reform and lead law-abiding lives and have been reviewing the services CRCs are providing for female offenders to ensure they meet contractual requirements. We are also working with partners in areas across England and Wales to develop whole system approaches to help female offenders turn away from crime and rebuild their lives. We will continue to robustly manage the CRC contracts to make sure they reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide the best value for money for the taxpayer.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-03T13:24:19.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622685/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622685/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Probation: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the findings of Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Probation, published in their report entitled A thematic inspection of the provision and quality of services in the community for women who offend, on 29 September 2016, whether she plans to re-establish dedicated funding for community services for women.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","50848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622686","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Government believes it is right that those who use the immigration tribunals and are subject to a fee should pay the full the cost of the service they receive.</p><p> </p><p>This is about making sure our courts and tribunals are properly funded, while reducing the cost to the taxpayer.</p><p>At the same time, we’re protecting the most vulnerable from any fee increase, including those who receive asylum support and cases involving children being supported or housed by a local authority.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-03T17:25:17.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622686/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622686/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the effect of changes to immigration and asylum tribunal fees on access to justice.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","50783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622687","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is committed to making sure that sentencing for those who kill or cause serious injury on the roads is proportionate within the context of our wider sentencing framework.</p><p> </p><p>It is our intention to commence a consultation before the end of the year which will look at driving offences and penalties.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","50797","2016-11-01T17:43:40.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622687/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622687/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Road Traffic Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will clarify the remit of the review into driving offences and penalties for drivers who cause death or serious injury to other people on the roads.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","50796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622688","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is committed to making sure that sentencing for those who kill or cause serious injury on the roads is proportionate within the context of our wider sentencing framework.</p><p> </p><p>It is our intention to commence a consultation before the end of the year which will look at driving offences and penalties.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","50796","2016-11-01T17:43:40.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622688/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622688/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Road Traffic Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the timescale is for the review into driving offences and penalties for drivers who cause death or serious injury to other people on the roads.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","50797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622689","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-03","<p>We are carrying out a comprehensive review of our probation reforms to improve outcomes for offenders and communities. Public protection is our top priority and we will not hesitate to take the necessary action to make sure our vital reforms are being delivered to reduce reoffending, cut crime and prevent future victims. As part of this review we will consider the services provided to female offenders by Community Rehabilitation Companies and the National Probation System.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-03T17:22:33.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622689/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622689/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Offenders: Rehabilitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if her Department's review of Transforming Rehabilitation addresses the effect of that policy on women; and when she plans to publish the findings of that review.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","50718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622690","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-02","<p>I have discussed this matter with the President of the Family Division, and the next steps are under consideration.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-02T13:43:24.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622690/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622690/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Family Proceedings: Judgements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions she has had with the President of the Family Division  on the issuance of new guidance on the anonymisation of judgments.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","50745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622691","Department of Health","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Department is committed to improving mental health treatment and support for young people in contact with the youth justice system.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England sets out in its Commissioning Intentions that it will deliver healthcare for children and young people detained by the justice system, including mental health treatment, to the standard set out in “Healthcare of Children and Young People in Secure Settings” developed in June 2013 by the Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health and others.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is developing a £24 million programme to address gaps in mental health provision for this vulnerable group.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-01T16:56:08.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622691/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622691/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-27","Young Offenders: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of mental health support available for youth offenders in the criminal justice system.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","50749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622692","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-09","<p>The Offender Rehabilitation Act 2014, which introduced licence and post sentence supervision for those serving short custodial sentences, applies to offences committed on or after 1 February 2015. Final proven reoffending data for those serving sentences imposed after the changes to the supervision of short sentences is not yet available. As with all new legislation, the operation of recall is kept under review.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","50839","2016-11-09T12:18:16.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622692/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622692/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-27","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate she has made of the cost to her Department over the last 12 months of expanding recall eligibility to those released from short prison sentences.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","50838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622693","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>In light of the Government’s manifesto commitment to achieve three million new apprenticeship starts in England by the end of the Parliament, the Cabinet Office will be centrally collecting data on apprenticeships to allow the Civil Service to report on its contribution towards the national target.</p><p> </p><p>One apprenticeship has been created in my Department to date. This is based in London and commenced in February 2016. I am therefore unable to comment on whether the apprentice will later secure a job in the Civil Service.</p><p> </p><p>As my department has 42 staff based in England this meets the apprenticeship target set by the Civil Service.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-11-01T15:12:12.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622693/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622693/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-27","Northern Ireland Office: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many apprenticeships have been created in his Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622694","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>My Department has not procured any steel, British or non-British, in the last 12 months.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-11-03T12:47:08.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622694/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622694/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-27","Northern Ireland Office: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent estimate he has made of the level of procurement of British steel by his Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622695","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Government will bring forward legislation in the next session that, when enacted, will repeal the European Communities Act 1972 and ensure a functioning statute book on the day we leave the EU. This Great Repeal Bill will end the authority of EU law and return power to the UK.</p><p>The Bill will preserve EU-derived legislation, as it applies in the UK on exit day. Once we have left the EU, parliament and the government will be able to make changes to the law in the usual way.</p><p>The Government will set out the content of the Bill and its implications in due course.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-11-04T14:15:27.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622695/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622695/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-27","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many EU laws, regulations and standards he plans to include in the planned Great Repeal Bill.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","50869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622696","Scotland Office","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Scotland Office has not procured any steel in the last 12 months.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-11-02T12:00:56.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622696/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622696/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-27","Scotland Office: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent estimate he has made of the level of procurement of British steel by his Department in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","50643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622697","Scotland Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly; all staff that join do so on an assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, principally from the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-11-03T13:04:18.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622697/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622697/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-10-27","Scotland Office: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many apprenticeships have been created in his Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622698","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-04","<p>The Transport Infrastructure Skills Strategy (January 2016) sets out our ambition to create 30,000 apprenticeships in the roads and rail sectors by 2020, in support of this government’s unprecedented investment in transport infrastructure. This target includes the Department for Transport, its Agencies and infrastructure client bodies – Crossrail, Transport for London, Highways England, Network Rail and HS2 Ltd, as well as each of their supply chains.</p><p> </p><p>Regarding apprenticeships just within the Department for Transport – comprising the central Department and the four Executive Agencies – data is not readily available in the format requested.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-04T11:03:53.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622698/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622698/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-27","Department for Transport: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many apprenticeships have been created in his Department in each region in each of the last five years; and how many participants in those apprenticeships subsequently secured a job within the Civil Service.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","50816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622699","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-01","<p>We are taking a series of measures to help commuters and others use carbon free transport, and will continue to promote public transport choices, supporting the market for innovative forms of transport and encourage a move to cleaner and lower carbon vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>By improving the whole journey, how each part connects and how to better integrate those parts, more people will have the choice to use greener transport for their journeys. For instance, the £30m Low Emission Bus Scheme will be funding over 320 Low Emission Buses in England over the period 2016-19. Furthermore, with the help of nearly £30m Government funding, we have trebled the number of cycle parking spaces at stations since 2010. We are spending more than £600 million by 2020 to support ultra low emission vehicles including significant funding to support the introduction of ultra low emission taxis.</p><p> </p><p>Cumbria County Council were allocated £4.89m from the Local Sustainable Transport Fund for 2011 to 2015 and just under £1m for 2015-16 to deliver high quality transport and connectivity improvements from key transport gateways in Cumbria to major visitor destinations. The Growth Deal agreed between Government and Cumbria LEP in July 2014 contained over £12m of funding for five projects that promote the use of sustainable transport, which included improved access to rail stations at Maryport and Workington, along with new cycling and walking infrastructure in Carlisle, Kendal and at key visitor attractions in the National Park.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-01T09:50:31.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622699/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622699/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-27","Public Transport: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to encourage commuters to use carbon-free public transport in (a) England and (b) Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","50799"
